See 4 spots. The two near the west have penumbras. Largest spot has two components and large penumbra. Spot near the E seems to have some whiter lines/ridges encircling it. These are the largest sunspots I've seen -- have been at solar minimum, and this is the largest sunspot for 3 years!
Primary A is quite bright white. B is brown-orange and dim. C is very faint, but seen with averted vision.
A, B very close; almost touching. A slightly brighter. C is farther and much dimmer. Nice triple.
8 stars. Makes a nice asterism. Near Pi-Ari. Est class III 2 p.
Wide split, medium bright stars. Should be able to split with a much smaller scope. All stars white.
Surprisingly dim -- found out that the secondary has started dewing up! Fairly wide split. All stars white. A brightest, BC and D just a little dimmer.
Cluster is bounded by a bright pentagon. Other stars faint to very faint. Est class II 3 p.
Very small and faint. Around a bright mag 6.8 double star. Only a few stars clearly seen, main fainter as a slight speckling with averted vision. Est class I 1 m.
Bright, spread out cluster. Marked star is orange. :) Est class II 3 m.
Medium-dim cluster, but seems fairly concentrated. Brightest stars form a jellyfish. Est class III 2 p.
Jupiter - just a white dot. All moons nicely positions as a pinpricks of light. Saturn - can see distinct circle of the planet, and ring structure.
Round, faint, but has a bright core. :) Bright star is Mirach.
Very faint. Circular. Mottled texture. Core brighter.
Extremely faint; only visible occasionally with averted vision. Faint nebulosity around 3 stars.
Faint, except for a few brighter stars. Sparse, strong central concentration. Est class I 3 p.
Can see two bands on Jupiter. Saturn: can see the rings in front and the shadow on the E side.
Bright core, almost stellar. Fades off in a 5:1 aspect ratio. M 32 is star-like but has slight nebulosity.
Small, slightly nebulous. With averted vision, see 3-4 star in a line through the center.
Jupiter - can see one band, hints of a second. Saturn - see rings distinct, but no detail. Jupiter is much brighter than Saturn.
Small blur. Fairly bright. Center is a little brighter.

Easy to locate with a smiley and triangle asterisms. M 38: Bright, center is somewhat concentrated. Hints of stars look like a faint globular. M 36: faint, diffuse, larger, less concentrated. Can only see with averted vision.
Small, bright. Next to M 36. Concentrated, lots of stars, medium variability. Est class I 2 r.
Bright and glittery. Stars white. See about 35 stars in the cluster.
Rough, generally lighter than nearby Mare Crisium and Mare Tranquilitatis.
Bright nebulosity around (apparently) 2 stars; N one is the Trapezium, other is sigma 2 Ori.  Fun region of the sky!
Large, easy to find. Has a mountain with two peaks in the middle. Flat base and rocky outside.
Edges of crater have some sharp peaks following the circle around.  Center has a nice bowl shaped crater with raised sides. Rimae visible.
Mars: very bright, peach color. Resolved as a very small disc. Uranus: star-like, slight blue tint.

Eratosthenes: flat floor, triangular shaped mountain in the middle. Lots of ridges on crater walls. Stadius: Just the rim of the crater is visible. Floor is flat, see some lunar rays from Copernicus. A few small craterlets inside, as well as a long chain outside.
Quite faint, just barely lighter than the sky. Next to a row of 3 stars (2 in view). Est class IX.
Has a snake of 6-7 stars, then a mist of fainter ones. Generally resolve with averted vision, though too hard to draw accurately. Est class II 2 m.
Quite faint. No stars resolved, just a slightly lighter patch. Near M 35. Est class II 1 r.
Small, modestly bright. Halfway between two mag 9 stars.  About 20 stars. Est class II 3 p.
About 10 modestly faint stars, and a cluster of much fainter ones (occasionally glimpsed with averted vision). Est class I 2 p.
Dim, spread out, sparse. About 30-40 stars. Est class II 2 p.
See 4 internal craterlets. Flat base, wide hilly, rough edges. Near Clavius.
Right next to Theophilus and Cyrilius. Floor looks pockmarked towards the E side.
Very bright star in the center. Roughly triangular shaped. :) Est class II 3 p.
Bright, small cluster. About 12 stars. Est class II 2 p.
4036: Modestly bright, elongated. Core is almost stellar. 4041: very faint, diffuse, round. One see occasionally.
Very small. Relatively bright core.
3982: very faint. round. Core is slightly brighter. 3998: very small, almost stellar. (Mistook for a star at first, but is slightly fuzzy.)
Appears as very faint nebulosity around a star.
Bright and obvious. See a Pythagorean theorem diagram in the pattern of stars. Lots of fainter stars in the view not drawn.
M46: very faint; slightly lighter patch. M47: Appears as nebulosity around 3-4 stars in the handle of a hockey stick. Bright.
Round fuzzy patch, slightly speckled with stars.
Large, bright circular haze, as of a rich cluster. 3 brighter stars. Marked star, eta Gem, is pale orange.
Moderately faint, sparkly-fuzzy patch. Brighter in the center. Fairly large.
M81: Dim, elongated, has brighter core. M82: small, thin, dim. Makes a triangle with two nearby stars.
Bright and small. Core is star-like.
Very faint lighter patch. Core is slightly brighter. Slightly eccentric.
Very bright core, star-like. Mottled texture, suspect two arms. [no, is elliptical]
Bright and concentrated. Almost looks like a class V globular. Bright star is yellow.
Very faint lighter patch. Center noticeably brighter. Slightly eccentric.
Very faint, only seen with averted vision. Core not very bright. Seems mottled.
Small, circular. Nearly stellar core. Pretty bright.
Brighter core. Speckled. Generally rather dim. Circular.
Small. Brighter core. Like a class V glob. Easily seen. Right next to a star.
Small. Stellar core. Fairly bright. Near M 106.
Round. Stellar core. Pretty bright.
Faint. Core not very bright. Slightly oval. Appears as a slightly lighter fuzzy patch.
Core is brighter. Rest is pretty dim. Perhaps a spiral galaxy? [yes!] Has some variation in texture.
Very faint, rich. Concentrated a little towards the center. Slightly sparkly appearance, but stars are too faint and numerous to resolve. Est class II 2 r.
Dim. Elongated. Core is somewhat brighter, occasionally appears as a fuzzy star with averted vision.
Small, dim. requires averted vision to see. Core a bit brighter.
Extremely faint. Round. Core not brighter.
Small, bright stellar core. Elongated.
Appears as nebulosity around a star.
4490: Bright, elongated, big. Core is brighter, sometimes seems to have two brighter patches. 4485: Very dim. Small, round. Only see occasionally with averted vision.
Small, round, very faint. Core slightly brighter.
Open cluster. See about 20 stars, some only intermittently. Slight central concentration. Est class II 2 p.
Very pretty - large and bright. Seems like some fractal-like pattern. Est class III 3 p.
Very faint, small. See only about 8 stars distinctly with averted vision. Fainter stars make a general glow. Est class II 2 m.
Bright and diverse. Prominent quadrilateral. Sparse. Est class III 3 p.
Really bright, sparse. Like it! Est class III 2 p.
Very faint. Small core is brighter, slightly elongated.
3227: faint, has a brighter core. Mostly seen with averted vision. Slightly elongated. 3226: Smaller and fainter. Round. See occasionally with averted vision.
3190: Elongated. Brighter core, stellar in the middle. 3193: small, round, bright core. Could not see 3187, which should also be in the FOV.
3686: Small. Quite faint. See occasionally with averted vision. Slightly brighter core. 3684: Small, very faint. See occasionally. Round, slightly brighter core.
Big, faint. See 10-20 stars, slightly concentrated at the center. Est class II 2 p.
Faint and large. Inner core stellar, outer core brighter and round.
Core is medium bright and circular. Outer part is faint and elongated.
Faint. Appears as nebulosity around a star.
Faint. Core slightly brighter. Slightly oval-shaped.
Dim. Core is brighter, almost stellar.
Large, faint oval patch. Core slightly brighter.
A: bright, has a slight yellow tint. B: orangey brown color. C: dim, white
A,D both bright white. Wide split even at low power. C: only seen with averted vision; faint. D: very faint, only see occasionally.
All stars white. A, D both very bright. B is dim but easy with direct vision. E is only visible with averted vision.
Pretty triple. :) Resolvable under low power (40x). All stars white, A med bright, B dim, C slightly dimmer.
A, B both very bright, white. A slightly brighter. C, D just white points. :)
All stars white. Easily split. Nice triple. A a little brighter. B, C very similar brightness.
Inside OCl NGC 2232. Primary very bright. B, C similar magnitude, dimmer.
A is brighter, B, C pretty faint, especially B. Close but nicely separated.

Part of M44! Always suspected lots of double stars here. Eng 37: order of brightness is A, B, D, C. S 571: Nice tight triple. Stars have similar brightness. A has a close companion requiring more magnification.
A, B are fairly close; didn't notice this was a double star until I looked closely. All stars are roughly equal brightness; all white.
Cool asterism; a double at the center of 3 corners of a square. C and D rather faint; A and B pretty bright. :)
AB is bright and yellow. C is cleanly split, and appears yellow-white. D is dimmer.
Primary white, secondary seems orangeish,  Saw this through a tree.
A very bright. B very dim, only see occasionally. C dim but easy with direct vision.
Nice little pattern of stars. Y is slightly yellow. A is maybe 1 mag brighter than B. C is very faint, only seen with averted vision.
Appears almost stellar with direct vision. With averted vision, appears as a small fuzzy patch with a bright core.
Very faint, only visible with averted vision. Core not very bright, maybe class VIII.
Stars here are faint, barely seen without averted vision.  3953 is a faint oval, more concentrated at the center. Best seen when moving the scope.
Right at zenith -- very hard to find!  Very faint, barely lighter than the sky. Large, uniform brightness.
Small, fairly bright; nearly stellar core.

Very faint. Had to close my eyes for a minute to be dark adapted enough to see. 4656 elongated; brighter core. 4657 only the core visible, and appears somewhat joined to 4656.  Near NGC 4631 (the Whale).
Dim, but bright core. Elongated, small.
Very faint, elusive; roundish. Core slightly brighter.
Very faint, dim. Med size, oval shaped. Almost appears sparkly/mottled
Small, elongated. Bright core
Dim, but brighter core. Roundish. Mottled texture. Core looks brighter vertically. A bar? [no]
Very faint, difficult. Core slightly brighter. Oval shaped. Only see occasionally.
Fairly bright. Bright core, elongated. Near a faint star.
4473: Bright, core is quite bright, stellar. Oval.  4477: Dimmer, very concentrated stellar core. Elongated a little.
Quite bright. Round, fuzzy. Core is brighter.
M 85: super big and bright. Bright core.  Looks grainy.  4394: small, faint, round. Stellar core.
Dim, though clearly seen with averted vision. Oval. Core is brighter.
Faint, small, elongated. Brighter core. Requires averted vision; only see occasionally.
Dim, elongated. Brighter core, almost stellar. Appears sparkly.
Round. Bright core. Appears elliptical. Easy to see with averted vision.
Very faint; elusive. Elongated. Core only slightly brighter. Slightly sparkly
Bright. Round core is concentrated. Small. [In fact, only seeing the bright core here; galaxy is larger.]
Faint, round. Core somewhat brighter. Appears stellar with averted vision.
Bright core. Can see with direct vision. Mottled, circular, like a faint globular.
Two bright stars in the center of a triangle. Primary and secondary similar brightness; see fair amount of turbulence about them.
Primary is bright, with a yellow tint. Secondary maybe has a faint hint of red. Nice line of 3 stars. :)
Very faint, diffuse, flat.
Brighter core, round. Outer part oval shaped. Mottled texture. Like to check this in darker skies.
Very bright core, star-like. Easy to see. Generally round, but near the core shape seems irregular.
Faint, elongated. Between two stars.
Faint. Elongated. Dim core. Elusive
4281: small, somewhat bright. Stellar core. Circular. 4273: very faint. Core diffuse. Oval.
Faint, small, bright core. Looks like a star with direct vision, but see some fuzziness with averted vision. Bright star is Cor Caroli
Very faint, elusive. Only see occasionally. Elongated in N/S direction. Core slightly brighter.
Very faint, small round, flat gray patch. Only seen with averted vision about 30% of the time.
Prom Agarum looks rough and rocky at the top, casts stark shadows down to Mare Crisium, which appears smooth and gray. Many dorsae are clear as raised ridges
Gray interior. Irregular rocky sides. Par bordering Lame has a double stepped wall. See some internal craterlets as dark spots
Rather bright. Brighter core, though not stellar. Rather like a faint class III globular.
Faint, but not hard with averted vision. Core is brighter, and sparkly. Core is circular, but hints that galaxy is elongated. Suspect spiral?
4550: small, dim, elongated. Stellar core. M 89: quite bright. Core is bright and stellar. Circular
Dim, but brighter circular core. Outer part elongated. Mottled texture. Spiral?
Large, elongated, very faint. Core not concentrated much. I suspect I'm partially looking through a roof, so using less than full aperture.
Very faint. Appears as slight nebulosity around a star, slightly offset.
Very bright concentrated core. Sparkly outer part, a bit amorphous. Spiral?
Fuzzy and round. Bright core. Overlaps a star. :)
Somewhat faint, bright stellar core. Core is round, but galaxy is oval-shaped.
Looks stellar with direct vision. With averted vision, see some mottled nebulosity. Oval shape.
Very small, elongated. Brighter core, though not stellar.
Small. Elongated. Bright, concentrated core. Though overall faint; best seen with averted vision.
Nice equally-spaced triple! :) B appears orangeish, A slightly yellow, C a little bluish.  A brightest, then C, then B.
Drawn slightly enlarged.  A, B have equal brightness. Both yellow. C is dim and white.
Very small, bright. Core is star-like. Looks slightly elongated.
Aristoteles: large. Flat basin. Rocky, uneven walls. One side of the wall very bright white. Mitchell: smaller, flat. Seems to have a bump in the middle.
A brightest, C nearly as bright, and B dimmer, sometimes appears slightly reddish.
A, B have nearly equal brightness and are wide enough to drive a proverbial truck through. C not too much dimmer.
Nice wide triangle; split in finder. A is bright; light gold color. B a little yellowish as well. C a magnitude dimmer.
A, B brighter and fairly close, but cleanly and easily split. C is dimmer, and D is very faint; can only see occasionally.  Saw a bright meteor pass through the field of view.
AB - unable to split. Can see some noisy Airy rings faintly. C is maybe 0.7 magnitude dimmer. D is very faint, but clear with averted vision.
A is very bright; pale yellow. C,D are white, similar magnitudes. B is very faint, need averted vision.
Part of a larger group of stars. ABC all pretty bright and easily split. Pretty! :)
Great asterism/multiple stars. Near M104. :) A,B,E,F are bright, D dimmer, and C is faint. E is slightly yellow.
Very bright, wide triple. Could likely see in the finderscope if sky were slightly darker. All stars white.
Primary, secondary nearly equally bright. C is dimmer.
5982: Star-like core, rest very dim. Slightly sparkly. Oval shaped. 5985: very dim, only see occasionally. Small faint, roundish core.
Very faint, long and thin. :) Most stars in FOV are pretty faint too; maybe mag 12.
Stellar core, core is modestly bright. Mottled appearance.
Dim. Brighter, nearly stellar core. Speckled appearance. Near a very faint [mag 13.7] star.
5363 is very bright, small, round. Stellar core. 5364 is extremely faint; only see occasionally as a slightly lighter patch.
Small. Stellar core. Looks like a fuzzy star.
Oval. Brighter core. Outer part dim but mottled. Hints of spiral arms? [No, is elliptical.]
Diffuse and faint; just a light patch. Center slightly brighter.
Faint, small. No stars resolved. Est class IV
Primary white. Secondary slightly orange brown. Other stars need averted vision to see.
Extremely faint. Only see occasionally. Elongated. Core not concentrated.
Extremely faint. See 50% of the time. Large, diffuse. Est class X.
Small. Faint (averted vision only). Concentrated center. No stars resolved. Est class V.

Very faint, lighter fuzzy patch; flat. No central star visible. Only seen with averted vision. No filter: invisible. UHC filter: faint gray patch. OIII filter: like UHC but everything darker and dimmer.  At higher mag (171x + UHC) is larger, but harder to distinguish from the background.

No filter: central star visible with averted vision, nothing else seen.  UHC filter: hints of nebulosity around the CS. CS is very faint (averted vision only). OIII filter: nothing visible.  Also tried 12mm + UHC; better framing with other field stars, but can't see nebula, and CS barely visible.
A is bright white. B is dim, barely visible with direct vision, though bright with averted vision. C is similar to B.
A, B similar magnitudes, though A is slightly brighter. Close, though nicely split at 140x. C is slightly dimmer. :)
Bright, wide triple. Nicely split at 28mm. Very near zenith right now.
Wide triple. Stars a little dim, but are all very similar magnitude.
Very nice, like a small star cluster. :)  C quite bright. A, B close, B rather dim. E, F med bright, G also very faint. Love it!
No filter: CS faint with averted vision. UHC filter: CS fainter. OIII filter: nothing visible. With 8mm + UHC, see faint light area around CS. Confirms observation from yesterday.
Small, faint. stellar core. Elongated. Averted vision required.
Very near M 13. Faint, small, brighter core. Oval shaped.
Flat base. Sharp black shadows. Small hill in the center. Rough outside the crater.

Mars: bright orange, barely resolvable as a disc. Moon. Lots of sharp small craters on the SW side, some detail on the dark side visible at this magnification; see Aristarchus (light) and Grimaldi (dark).  Very cool and unplanned.
A slightly brighter than B. C is much dimmer, best seen with averted vision.
A, B very tight. B is maybe two magnitudes dimmer than A. A little tricky. D is much dimmer, best seen with averted vision. Can't detect C component; should be above B and very faint.
Very bright, easy to see. Est class VIII.
Two small sunspots. Larger one a little elongated; smaller is just touching the larger.  At higher mag (50x), can see 3 more nearby spots in a triangle.

No filter: bright white spot, slightly fuzzy edges. Easily seen with direct vision. No CS visible. UHC filter: still bright, seems to have a larger faint halo, and is no longer circular. OIII: dimmer, view more similar to no filter. Increasing mag to 167x gives slightly larger cleaner view with UHC.
No filter: looks like a bright star, direct vision. With UHC: appears brighter than the other stars, more of a bright disc with soft edges. No CS visible.
A, B bright, wide split, visible at low power. A has a slightly yellow tint, B slightly bluish. C is rather faint.
Beta-Oph just outside the FOV to the W. Very bright, loose, sparse wide cluster. Nicely framed here. Stars in the center form a sideways 8. Est class II 2 m.
One bigger spot with a very faint one next to it. Another smaller one on the other side.
Two spots. One near the edge is darker; the one closer to the center is gray.
Spot a little elongated, curved. At higher mag, resolves into 3 spots.
Two spots near the center.
One spot near the E side. Under higher mag can see it has a penumbra.
Spot is very dark, penumbra faintly visible.
Arago not quite circular- has a little circular cutout. It has 3 small mountains inside. Alpha and beta are smooth, roundish hills.

At 8mm, seen without filter as an irregular nebulosity around a star. With UHC is brighter patch around a star, elongated. OIII - small bright oval, nothing resolved. Higher power too dim to see much. Best seen with averted vision; direct vision only see hints (with UHC). Also put in a neutral density filter by mistake. Seen only as a faint blur. :)
Somewhat dim, diffuse, though bright spot at core. No stars resolved. Est class III.
One spot, easy to see penumbra.
Big. Flat bottom, darker gray interior. Mostly encircled with light rough area. Nearby small craterlet with sharp contrasty walls.
A looks bluish, B reddish. Very close, not cleanly separated. C, D bright wide split, can easily seen in low power eyepiece (40x). Great multiple star!
A, B quite bright. C is faint, only seen with averted vision.
Wide enough to be split at 40x, but C was too dim to see. A is slightly golden, B, C white. C is faint but still seen with direct vision.
Right next to M 107. A bright, C bright, B dim, D very faint, only averted vision.
Small spot with clear penumbra. Round.
See one sunspot and a thin fractal line on the opposite side (rather faint, white). Also some white lines encircling the spot. [Lines are called faculae.]

Mare Marginis (Sea of the edge) appears as a darker line, near, but not touching the edge of the moon. Same brightness as Mare Crisium. Mare Smythii (Smyth's Sea) thin; has a darker patch, rest lighter than Mare Marginis. Langrangeneus - soft whiter area, white dot in the very center. Mare Australae (Southern Sea): large, uneven shape, wider near the southern side. Separated from the edge of the moon. Gray interior. Proclus: is bright white, with contrasty lunar rays. Golclenius is a bright white ring with gray interior. Mare Humboltatum (Sea of Humboltatum) has somewhat of a D shape. Mare Undarum (Sea of Waves): patchy, darker areas generally the shape of an epsilon.
Two small spots seen. At higher powers, resolve to 4.

UHC: bright, round, like a slightly defocused star. Direct vision, no CS seen. With no filter: maybe invisible? According to the star atlas, there's a star, fainter than A, just next to the PN which is now visible. With UHC filter, seems this star is obscured.

No filter: seen with averted vision as a faint small round patch, concentrated in the middle. No CS. UHC: similar but a bit more obvious, visible with direct vision. OIII: ball shape is more clear, but everything is rather dim.
No filter: very faint, barely seen with averted vision; star-like. UHC: more obvious, still star-like with averted vision.
No filter: star-like, direct vision. UHC: much brighter (relatively); appears brighter than star B, especially with averted vision. OIII: dim, hard to see.
3 spots. Penumbra on largest one.
Very sparse OC. Grid-like spacing of stars. See 11-12 stars. Est class III 3 p.

Can't see without a filter. With UHC, occasionally see a hint of a gray patch with averted vision. No CS. Increasing mag to 173x helps a little; can see more often, though still very faint. OIII filter: can't see anything.
One big, dark spot, with prominent penumbra and tendrils coming off! Also 2 more faint spots.
Very sparse OC. 5 prominent stars in the shape of a trapezoid. Est class II 3 p.
Loose, poor cluster. Somewhat faint. Stars appear in several chains. Est class I 1 p.
Within M8 (which shines through the light pollution with an OIII filter, but not shown here). Very bright, open. Very nice! Maybe 30 stars. Est class II 3 p.
Sparse open cluster, large variability in magnitudes. 3 bright stars in a triangle and another 3 as part of a chain. Est class III 3 p.
Cassini band clear. Can see a large band near the equator, slightly brownish, and the polar area slightly blue.
No filter: appears stellar, faint with direct vision. UHC: brighter, other stars fade out. OIII: even brighter, other stars invisible. No CS seen.

No filter: invisible. UHC: visible as a lighter patch with averted vision. OIII: brighter, still averted vision only. Appears as a round ball, brighter in the center. Hints of a ring structure. No CS visible.
No filter: invisible. UHC: faint, but direct vision. Amorphous shape. Brighter towards the W side. No CS visible. OIII: similar to UHC but everything dimmer.
3 spots visible. One large, two small Large one resolves to three under high power.
No filter: stellar, direct vision. UHC: stellar, slightly brighter relative to other stars. OIII: even brighter (brightest of all in the view). Still stellar.
4 bright stars, and another 10-15 dimmer ones. Est class II 3 p.
No filter: faint, stellar with direct vision. Very rich star field. UHC, OIII: successively dim the other stars, PN is easy to identify. Still stellar, maybe slightly fuzzy.
Very bright, large cluster. Two brightest stars are delta1 and delta2 Lyr. Delta2 (marked) is yellow. Est class II 3 m.
Medium bright, well separated cluster. About 40 stars. Est class III 3 p. Atlas indicates cluster is in the circle, which doesn't look like a cluster, only a few random stars.

Obvious (even at low power) without a filter. Bright ring, interior is brighter than the surrounding sky. Cannot see CS. Adding UHC filter increases contrast a little, but unfiltered view is best. OIII filter leaves everything dim and blurry.
No filter: invisible. UHC: faint patch, core is brighter, only seen with averted vision. No CS visible. OIII: slightly brighter, but everything pretty dim.
No sunspots. Very faint light faculae on the W side.
Very faint. Next to a mag 10 star. See 8 stars with averted vision, and flickers of a few more. Est class II 2 p.
Very faint. Took several attempts to see this. Core a bit brighter (likely I'm seeing only the core here.)  Est class III.
No filter: small, somewhat bright, though averted vision only. CS visible. UHC: very bright, can see with direct vision. CS still visible. Looks larger.
No filter: appears stellar. UHC: very faint, small, but brighter. Appears as nebulosity around a star. Averted vision only.
Sparkly! Maybe 50 stars, similar brightness. Fairly bright (at med high powers). Est class II 1 m.
Very small and faint. Poor cluster. Only a few stars seen with averted vision. Est class III 1 p.
Small, bright cluster. Concentrated. Brighter foreground stars with a haze of fainter ones. :) Est class I 3 r.
Small, faint, not very concentrated. No stars resolved. Near Kaus Borealis. Est class X.
Not seen at lower powers or without filter. With UHC, appears as a small faint patch, a little brighter in the center. Averted vision only. No CS.
One spot near the E side. Faint faculae nearby.
Venus - bright, gibbous. Mars - faint, pink, circular.
Very bright, rich cluster, concentrated in the center. Three brighter stars in the foreground. Darker patches of dust obscuring the cluster. :) Est class I 2 r.
Small, poor cluster. About 10 brighter stars and a scattering of fainter ones.. Est class II 3 p.
One small spot. No penumbra.
Two clusters of spots. See 10 total.
Several clusters! The NW cluster has white rings (faculae) around it
One double spot, and one very faint one near the S.
No filter: bright, small, resolves as a tiny disc. Greenish. UHC filter: a bright solid disc, slightly fuzzy at the edges. Larger. No CS visible.
No filter: star-like, faint, but direct vision. Hard to know which point was the PN. UHC: still star-like, but brighter, easier. OIII: to dim to see much of anything.
Fairly large and bright. Easy. Mix of brighter and fainter stars, not too concentrated. Pretty nice. Fainter stars at edge of visibility not shown. Est class II 2 m.
Very small. 3 bright stars and some nebulosity of many much fainter stars. Assuming the nebulosity is the cluster, est class II 1 r.
Primary very bright, secondary also bright, ternary very faint.
Fairly large, bright, some concentration. Est class II 2 p.

3 bright glittery cluster. Stars like diamonds. :) 6871: very bright, several double stars. Est class III 3 p. B1: fainter, about 20 stars, spread out. Est class III 2 p. B2: similar to B1, but a little smaller and dimmer. Est class III 2 p. NGC 6883 at the edge of the view on the E.
Bright, compact cluster with Y shaped chains of stars. Est class II 3 p.
Large, very faint gray patch, fairly uniform. Occasionally see hints of individual stars. Est class III 1 r.
Small, concentrated. Large variation in star brightness. Est class I 3 p.
No filter: invisible. UHC: large, fairly bright; easy with averted vision, difficult with direct vision. No CS. Roundish, slight irregular shape. Some ring structure. Top half a little brighter.
No filter: stellar, direct vision. UHC: stellar, about the same brightness relative to other stars. OIII: still stellar, but relatively much brighter.
Very faint, small Mottled texture. Hints of lots of faint stars. Somewhat concentrated. Est class II 2 r.
Very big, bright, and sparkly! Right somewhat concentrated. Amazing. Faintest stars make lighter patches that kind of look like rose petals, hence the name. Est class II 3 r.

At 141x, no filter: appears stellar, blinks out with direct vision. UHC filter makes it show up better. At 250x: similar, but can see direct vision without a filter.  With UHC: still stellar.  No CS visible.

Halfway between two brighter stars (mags 9, 11). No filter: very faint, transparent gray patch, brighter in the center. Visible with direct vision, barely. UHC: makes the PN more concrete. Faint ring visible, also see CS sometimes. :)
No filter: stellar with direct vision. UHC: still stellar, but brighter. Some fainter stars in the FOV not drawn.
Small, difficult, extremely faint. Only see occasionally as a grainy ball, somewhat concentrated. Hard to determine number of stars. Est class II 1 m. More stars at the edge of visibility not drawn.
No filter: stellar. Faint, but direct vision. At lower power would blink out with direct vision. UHC filter: stellar, brighter (slightly).
No filter: invisible. UHC: very faint blur, concentrated at the center. Averted vision only. OIII filter: possibly slightly brighter (relatively), but everything very dim.
No filter: stellar, very faint, can barely see with averted vision. UHC: stellar, easier to pick out, can see with direct vision.
No filter: faint, stellar. Averted vision only. UHC: appears fairly bright, but disappears with direct vision. Seems to have a slight size, maybe elongated E-W a little. No CS.

No filter: obvious. Looks like a small faint globular cluster, maybe class III. Concentrated at the center. No CS. Averted vision only. UHC: slightly brighter, edge seems more defined, but like the unfiltered view more.
Fairly small, very faint. Not very concentrated. Appears with averted vision as a speckled gray patch. Est class II 2 m.
Sparse, fairly bright. Somewhat separated from background stars. Est class III 2 p.
Small, very faint. Appears as speckling around 2-3 brighter stars. Est class II 2 p.
Appears as a faint speckled haze around a cluster of about 12 brighter stars. Est class II 3 r.
Bright, concentrated, small. Has 3 brighter stars visible at low power. Est class I 3 p.
Sparse. Looks like a question mark. Est class II 2 p.

No filter: small, quite bright, oval-shaped, fuzzy edges. Easy even without averted vision to see. No detail or CS visible. UHC filter: super bright, edges harder, no internal detail. OIII filter: similar, but field stars are almost invisible. Target could take more magnification if the seeing were better.
Poor, small cluster. Brightest stars make a D or an O shape.

No filter necessary! Big, bright with averted vision, CS faintly visible. Center is brighter, then edges are fuzzy. Like a class VI globular. With direct vision, PN fades substantially, occasionally disappearing, leaving only the CS visible, and sometimes a faint ring structure.
Vaguely shaped like an "8". Bright, loose cluster, easily seen even at low power. About 20 stars. Est class III 3 p.
Brighter stars make a mini Cygnus. A number of very faint stars concentrated near the middle. Overall somewhat dim.  Est class I 3 p.
Very big, bright, loose cluster. Star in the center is a triple star. About 60 stars. Est class II 3 m.
Dim, most stars need averted vision to see. But two bright mag 10-11 stars. Poor cluster, maybe only 20 stars. Est class III 3 p.
Primary (A) bright white. C is orangeish. B is very close to a, and brighter than C. Nice bright triple!
A, E, C all bright, and easily split at low power (40x). B is very faint, close to A. D is also very faint, and quite close to C. :)
Modestly large, quite faint. About 30 stars. Est class II 2 p.
Near M15. A, B about equal brightness and quite close, though cleanly separated. C is dimmer.

No filter: see CS, faintly with averted vision. With UHC: see small very faint blur about 50% of the time, averted vision only. No CS visible (though drawn in the picture from no filter view). Located at the fourth corner of a square made by 3 other stars.
A, B can split at low power (40x). Estimate A is 1 mag brighter than B, and B is 2 mags brighter than C
Large faint gray path, circular. Core not much brighter. Speckled with stars like a faint open cluster.
Fairly bright, small cluster. About 14 brighter stars and many dimmer ones. :) Est class II 3 p.
Very small, bright, concentrated, poor. 9 stars. Est class I 3 p.
Small, not too bright. 4 stars in the shape of a trapezoid and a few dimmer ones clustered in the middle. Est class I 2 p.
Very small, concentrated. Looks like a faint class I globular.

No filter: invisible. UHC filter: occasionally hints of a faint gray patch, rather unsure if I see it or not. OIII: very faint gray patch, can see with averted vision most of the time. No CS or other details resolvable.
Bright, open cluster. Loose small and compact at low power. About 20 stars. Est class II 2 p.
5 brighter stars in a rough question mark shape, and about 25-30 fainter ones. Est class III 3 p.
Triangular-shaped cluster, like a mini M39. Est class III 3 p.
Bright, large, spread out. Encircled by 5 brighter stars. About 50 stars. :)  Est class II 1 m.
No filter: looks stellar, direct vision. UHC: Appears slightly brighter, slightly larger with direct vision, and substantially brighter with averted vision.

No filter: very bright. Circular. Larger and brighter with averted vision. Disc-like, though perhaps the edge is slightly brighter. No CS seen. At lower power (94x) had distinct blue color. UHC: similar, though edges a little sharper and overall brighter. OIII: bright disc, no details seen.

No filter: light gray patch, brighter in the center, averted vision only, no CS. UHC: brighter (still averted vision only). Round, center brighter and has a faint halo around it. OIII: visible, but everything rather dark.
No filter: invisible. UHC: large, very faint patch. Circular. Only seen with averted vision. Moving the scope helps a lot here. Slightly brighter in the center, no CS seen.
Looks like a chicken's foot or a claw. Creepy. Small, fairly bright, slightly concentrated. Est class II 3 p.
No filter: bright, stellar. However, blinks out with direct vision, much like NGC 6826. UHC: slightly brighter with averted vision. Still blinks out with direct vision.
Poor, concentrated towards the center. About 20 stars. Not too exciting. Est class I 2 p.
Large, sparse cluster. 3 bright stars, and about 25 total. Bright star in the center  has a yellow tint. Est class II 3 p.

Bright, even with direct vision. At 40x appears stellar. At 250x appears as a round flat fuzzy ball. Hints of ring structure, no CS. UHC: slightly brighter, ring structure a little more apparent. Wish I had a higher power eyepiece for this. OIII. visible, but everything too dark.
Star hopped here starting from Saturn! Bright, star-like at 40x. No filter: fuzzy, oval shaped, center slightly brighter. Easy with direct vision. No CS. UHC: much brighter, but no more detail.
AB, C is a wide split even at 40x. At 250x, A, B are nearly touching. They are both white, and about equal magnitude. C is a little dimmer (1 mag?). :)

Invisible with no filter and with UHC filter. OIII: large, extremely faint ring visible, averted vision only. No CS seen. However, going back to no filter I can see the CS. Increasing the magnitude to 141x helps; can see both the PN and the CS with the OIII filter. Cool. I want darker skies to see this again. :)
A, B close, but easily split (even split at 94x). A, B, about equal magnitude.  C is very faint, only seen with averted vision. D is bright.

No filter: seen clearly at 141x with averted vision. At 250x, invisible with direct vision, but averted vision shows a bright small ball concentrated in the center, like a tiny globular. PN is right next to a star of about equal magnitude. With UHC: significantly brighter, a little bigger, seen with direct vision. Center is very bright, I think it is the CS. :)
Has about 10 brighter star, another 10 medium ones, and a concentrated center of fainter stars. Est class I 3 m.
Very faint gray patch. Appears slightly sparkly. Have to move the scope to see this, only see 50% of the time. Tried 141x, but I think the higher magnification helps a bit here.

No filter: appears as a light halo around a star at 141x. Relatively bright, but averted vision required. At 250x, is a little more defined. Interior is ever so slightly brighter than the background, and a ring is evident. UHC: brightens up the interior quite a bit, making the ring harder to see. Prefer unfiltered view. Really great. :)
Two bright stars, about 15-20 dimmer ones. Concentrated. Est class I 3 p.
A little faint, hard to pick out originally. Has about 15 dim stars and 15 dimmer ones. Concentrated. Originally appeared nebulous until I looked closely. Est class I 2 p.
Right next to a bright "backward F" shaped asterism, easy to find a low power. Cluster is sparse and dim, about 10 stars. Est class II 2 p.
Small light patch. Only see with averted vision. No stars resolved.  Many more stars not drawn.
Two bright stars. Cluster a bit difficult to pick out from the background field. Est class IV 2 p.
No filter: appears stellar at 141x with averted vision. At 250x, still stellar. Adding UHC filter, stellar but relatively brighter. Can see with direct vision, barely.
No filter: fairly bright, stellar. Seen almost direct vision at 141x. At 321x, with direct vision. UHC filter: still stellar, appears as bright as star B.
Easy double in this scope. Primary is light gold. Secondary is white, almost grayish blue, only a little dimmer.
AB bright, not able to split. C and D about equal magnitude.
A, B together are much brighter than C. A is a little brighter than B.
Small. Relatively faint. Round, fuzzy. Center is concentrated, almost star-like.
Bright, star-like. With averted vision see some nebulosity.
Extremely faint, slightly lighter fuzzy patch. Not concentrated. See 25-30% of the time.

Small, almost stellar at first glance, though can see a semi-circle shape. Higher power confirms that Venus is about at half phase. Dark side is slightly darker than the background sky.  Measured using shadows and the telescope angle that Venus is about 45 from the sun.
Faint, misty cluster of stars. A bit elongated. A few stars very bright, most require averted vision to resolve. Est class II 3 p.
Very dim stars. Sparse and spread out, but center is concentrated. Had to stare at this a while before I could see the cluster. Est class I 2 p.
Very small. Highly concentrated. Requires high power to see. Between two brighter (mag 10, 11.5) stars. Est class I 1 p.
Very small and rather faint. Concentrated. Easy to see 3 stars with averted vision, the rest only pop in and out of view at the edge of detectability. Est class I 2 p.
Extremely faint stars at the edge of detection, scattered loosely around 3 magnitude 13ish stars. Difficult. Est class III 2 p.
Bright, sparse, big. Hard to identify as a cluster. Brighter stars make a trapezoid. Est class III 2 p.

Noticed/discovered this serpentine curve of about 20 stars on the way to searching for King 16. Not sure what to call it; part of it looks like a 2, also could be a t-shirt or a vase.  Maybe "omega snake"? Berkeley 4 is on the W end of it, seen as 3-4 stars. RA: 00 47 9.5; Dec 64 31 11.3
Extremely faint, big. Appears as a long thin band of nebulosity.
Bright, fairly large. Some stars resolved. Concentrated towards the center. Est class II 2 m.
Faint. Center is brighter. Core appears circular, the outer part oval (slight) elongated N-S.
Not very concentrated. Fainter stars appear nebulous unless I look closely at them with averted vision. Brighter stars make a spiral shape. Est class III 3 p.
Strongly concentrated. Most stars are very faint. Four stars form a backward Y in the center. Est class I 2 p.
Visible at low power. Small, bright, concentrated. 6 bright stars in the center make a mini Cassiopeia. Like it! Est class II 3 p.
Bright, wide split, seen easily at 40x. All stars roughly equal magnitudes. Nice.
Nice quadruple. A, B both very bright and quite close; about 1 star-width between them, in moments of better seeing. C is rather faint, D seems brighter.

A bright, B dim, and C extremely faint, only seen occasionally with averted vision. Fog came in very quickly (within 2-3 minutes) while observing this; I was seeing the triple just as well at 141x before the fog, then needed higher power to cut through while making the sketch.
AB bright, can't separate. C is slightly brighter than D, both close together, appeared initially as a single star.
Extremely faint. Slightly oval gray patch. Not much concentrated at the center. Detected at 141x, but additional magnification helps make this easier to see. Moving the scope helps.
Makes an equilateral triangle with two mag 7 stars. Large, dim, core diffuse. Appears speckled - perhaps some mag 13-14 foreground stars?
2:1 aspect ratio. Core is brighter. Uneven texture; hints of two curved arms in a backward S. One on the N side more prominent.
Large, oval, somewhat faint. Center brighter and circular. Elliptical?
Very faint glow. Center not concentrated.
Big, very bright. Elongated. Very nice!
Somewhat faint. Diffuse. Appears as a light patch. No stars resolved. Est class IX
584 on the W side. Bright, small, very bright core. 596 on the E side. Also bright, small with a stellar core. Dimmer than 584.
Small, fairly bright. Oval shaped. Core is a little brighter.
Bright. A bit elongated. Core is brighter, not stellar but circular.
Faint. Fairly large, elongated. Appears as a nebulous glow.

At 141x, appears almost stellar, possibly a faint haze around it, with averted vision. Increasing mag to 250x, still stellar with a faint nebulosity.  UHC filter shows the PN much brighter, though still requires averted vision. No CS.
Looks like a scorpion with some imagination. Big, sparse. Not super-bright. About 30 stars. Est class II 3 p.
Very hard to find in the southern murk. Too many lights. A is bright white, C is med bright white. C faint, maybe brownish? Wide split.
Very large crater between the edge and Sinus Iridum. Walls are rough. Flat basin. One larger internal craterlet, and two smaller ones seen.
A = Zeta Per is super bright. B is a small pinprick. C is super-faint, especially in the glare of A. Averted vision only. D, E are med bright, maybe one magnitude brighter than B.
Wide, easy split, saw at 141x. C is pretty dim.

Nice double double! Can see at low power (40x). STF 401 is on the S side, stars about equal magnitudes. STFA 7 is on the N side. A, B are bright, C is very dim, could only see by increasing to 321x and staring with averted vision.
A is Alcyone, in the middle of the Pleiades. B, C, D are fairly bright. G, H are faint. F is very faint (or lost in the glow of A). Can't see E star, which should be between F and A.

ObjIds: STF 373 AB, STTA 33 AC, STU1 AD
Notes: A, C bright, about equal brightness. B close to A and just a dot.

A very bright. C medium. B is extremely faint, only see occasionally with averted vision (difficult!). Increasing to 321x helps a little. At lower power, A, C and 3 other stars make a sickle asterism. (Last star outside the FOV.) A = Gamma Cam.
Nice double double! A,B bright, about the same magnitude. C dim, D, E closer and bright.
A very bright, other stars quite faint.
A very bright, BC dim. D, E both very faint, averted vision only. Would be visible at low power under darker skies.
Wide split. A fairly bright, B a medium dot. C is quite faint, need averted vision to see. Discovered afterwards that the secondary mirror is dewing up. C is mag 11.4 and should be easier to see.

Nice mini-cluster of stars. Can't separate A,B. They are only 0.5" apart, and would need better seeing and higher power. Can't separate C,D either. From brightest to dimmest: AB, F, E, CD, I.  I can only be seen occasionally with averted vision.
Near Alnitak. A double triple! Wow! 762: AB = sigma Ori, is very bright. Then D, then C. 761: Stars dimmer than STF 762. A slightly brighter than B, C, which are about equal magnitudes.
AB nearly impossible to split. Possibly hints of B occasionally in diffraction ring. C is dim, best with averted vision.
Nice group of spots on the E side. Only see two regularly due to clouds.
Small, faint, concentrated. Appears as a single star at first glance. Est class I 2 p.
1746: Very large, bright, sparse. Not very concentrated. Maybe 30 stars. Est class III 3 p. 1750: a sub-cluster of 1746. Doesn't stand out as separate. About 12 stars. Est class IV 2 p.
Bright, wide triple. Visible at low power (40x). A has a slight gold color. B, C white.
Very cool - 4 stars in a line. In order of brightness: A, B, D, C. C is much fainter than the others.
3 stars in a line. A, C are split at low power. B is faint.
A,B are fairly close. A fairly bright. B, C about equally dim.
A bright. Split A, C at 141x easily. But couldn't detect B except at high power. B is very faint, averted vision only.
Large. Flat bottom. Several large craterlets inside, one with double walls (P). Rough sides with several crevasses. Craterlet S is bowl shaped.
Large, bright, sparse. About 30 stars. Est class III 3 p.
Leaf-shaped cluster or upside down tree. Several double stars, including the brightest star in the cluster (iota-Ori). Bright and sparse. Est class II 3 p.
Nebulosity around a star. No structure, but diminishes radially. UHC filter doesn't help. Central part bright enough to see with direct vision.
Very bright, slightly mottled nebulosity. Not especially brighter at the center.
No filter: appears stellar, can see with direct vision. UHC filter: appears brighter, still stellar.  At 166x, possibly resolves as a small disc.
Small, faint, concentrated.  All but 2 stars only seen intermittently with averted vision. Appears almost as nebulosity. Had a hard time finding this cluster.  Est class I 2 p.
Large. Two hills in the middle. Several craterlets in the middle. Mountainous walls. Superimposed over another crater of about the same size. Pretty cool.

With 8mm (141x) appears stellar. At 250x, no filter still stellar, seen with direct vision.  Adding UHC filter: possibly a hint of nebulosity, but not much. OIII filter brings out nebulosity a lot. CS still seen with averted vision. Faintest hint of a ring structure visible.
7 brighter stars, about 15-20 dim ones. Concentrated, easy to spot. Est class I 3 p.

No filter: appears stellar; faint with direct vision. UHC: stellar but brighter. OIII: similar to UHC, but everything is dimmer. Filters make J320 appear brighter than star X; otherwise it's much dimmer.
1807 is on the SW side; 1817 is on the NE side. Both clusters very sparse, slight concentration, fairly bright, easy to see at low power. 1807 Est class II 2 p. 1817 Est class III 2 p.
Very bright and big. Has a distinctive asterism with 3 stars in a line between 2 very bright stars. Marked star is lambda-Ori. Est class II 3 p.
No filter: seen with averted vision as a somewhat faint soft gray disc. No details or CS visible. With UHC: brightens up considerably. See brighter inner part and dimmer outer. No CS. Very nice.
Very bright, small. Easy to see even at low power. Stars sparkly. Forms an upside-down 37. Fun! Est class III 2 p.

Mare Crisium a darker gray, but has some variability due to dorsae (lighter lines) and lunar rays, especially from bright white Proclus (with grayer center). Other small unidentifiable craters around the perimeter are white dots. In general, outside Mare Crisium is lighter gray, pockmarked with white dots/arcs. Mare Angius appears as a long wavy line.

Billy: flat basin, dark gray interior. Walls are quite even and circular, well-defined. Hansteen: Interior same color as outside. Rougher walls, slight terracing. Has a craterlet in the middle. Has some rocky, white fractal ridges going out from the south side.
Extremely faint, small. Only see the round core. Rest of the galaxy should be much larger, but invisible here.
Primary (A) several magnitudes brighter than secondary (B). Secondary seems to have an orange color. C is brighter than B and a very wide split.
A is bright, nice orange color. C is fairly bright. B and D both very faint, B requires averted vision to see.
A, B about equal brightness. Fairly close together. Nice pair! C is farther away and fainter.
A, B very tight split, clean though. A is white, B orangeish. C is dim.
Has 2 bright, 6-8 medium, and many fainter stars. The bright star in the center is orange. Est class II 3 p.
No filter: appears stellar with direct vision. UHC: brighter, hints that this is a disc. OIII: very dim overall, no more detail than with UHC.
See 4 bright stars and a haze around them. Est class II 3 ?
Quite faint, slightly lighter patch in the sky. Hints of speckled stars. Took 3 attempts to see this! Two brighter stars SW of A useful for locating the cluster. Est class II 1 r.
4-5 dim stars, and a slight, extremely faint gray patch. No other stars resolved. Very difficult. Est class III 1 r?
Nice cluster! Small, not too dim. Wide range of star magnitudes. Somewhat concentrated. General nebulosity around the brighter stars. Est class II 3 r.
A, B about equally bright. Easily split even at 40x. C is faint, need averted vision to see.
Bright wide triple. Easy. A, C split easily at 40x. B is a bit dimmer.
A, C quite bright, A is a little brighter. B is very faint, hard to see, close to A.
Difficult. Very faint. Appears as a soft speckled glow, somewhat concentrated. Est class II 2 r.
Super wide, bright triple. A and C about equally bright, B a little dimmer.
Nice bright cluster with a large range of magnitudes. :) Est class III 3 p.

Tau CMa (A) is the brightest star in NGC 2362. D is fairly bright. B, C are both near A and quite dim; only see with averted vision.  NGC 2362 has a triangular shape. Bright and concentrated. Like it! Est class II 3 p.
Hazy, speckled patch. Has a few slightly brighter stars. A little concentrated. Est class II 2 m

Cauchy: rim looks like a doughnut, round  and bulgy. Small. Rupes Cauchy is a slightly wavy dark line. Tau and Omega are faint small bumps. Couldn't see Rima Cauchy, which should be between Cauchy and D. Drawn from memory as clouds moved in just after I started.

Four clusters of sunspots. A: has a clear penumbra, and a smaller spot nearby. B: a double spot with penumbra. C: 4 small spots. D: 4 small spots; one on the east side has two little chains of gray spots coming off it.
Plinius is round, with raised walls, mountainous on the outside. Sharp shadows. Rimae Plinus (in darker band) not seen.
Appears as a faint glittery patch.
Small, faint fuzzy patch. Slightly elongated.
Small, concentrated. Maybe 8 brighter stars (at  least near the center) and then a haze of fainter ones. Est class I 3 m.
Large, very bright, sparse. About 25-30 stars. Appears as a part of a larger cluster about 1.5 degrees wide, seen at low power. Est class II 2 p.
General triangular shape, like a 3-vaned pinwheel. Med bright, sparse. :) Est class II 2 p.

Palus Epidemiarum (Marsh of Epidemics) has the darker Mare color. Has 5 larger craters in or bordering it. Has some small hills and white patches. Most interesting region is crater Capuanus, with uneven-thickness walls  and 3 finger-like hills coming away from it.
Really big, bright. General distorted heart-shape with brighter stars, and some fainter stars in the interior. :) Est class II 3 p.
Two brighter stars, rest fainter. Not very concentrated. Very near M 47. About 40 stars. Est class III 2 p,.

Near the edge of M 46. Cannot see without a filter. With UHC, see a round fuzzy ball, almost with direct vision. No details, or CS seen. OIII filter: brighter, more obvious against background stars. Think I see a ring structure.

Foucault is bowl-shaped and has a raised rim. Harpalus: very round, also bowl-shaped. Shadows appear somewhat like a yin-yang symbol. Montes Foucault (Foucault Mountains) are straight and thin, and just a bit longer than Foucault itself.

Bright. Appears stellar at 40x. At 141x, no filter, is direct vision, and appears as a round gray ball, brighter in the center. With UHC filter, similar but slightly larger and brighter. With OIII, center is brighter but all other stars are gone.
At 141x, no filter, appears stellar, not quite direct vision, but easy with averted vision. Still stellar but brighter with UHC. Adding OIII was about the same as with the UHC. Still stellar at 250x.
Faint nebulosity around a star, more on the W side. Not visible without a filter. Using an OIII filter makes this a bit brighter.
Small, faint, concentrated. I see a small patch of a lot of stars near the center. Est class I 3 p.
Small hazy patch next to a triangle of 4 stars. Looks sparse, but has a faint glow indicating lots of stars. Est class I 3 m.
Cool triple triangle shape, or a triangle of triangles. :) Est class II 2 p.

At 141x and no filter, bright, looks like a fuzzy star. At 250x, bright round ball, direct vision. Brighter in the center. With UHC, very bright, especially in the center. Perhaps this is a CS? Love this one.
Lots of extremely faint stars giving a slight glow. Not too concentrated. Est class II 1 m.

No filter: seen clearly with averted vision. Brightish center - maybe the CS? and a fainter haze around it. Adding a UHC filter brightens it considerably at the center, almost like a small ball. Suspect that I'm not seeing the CS, since it got so much brighter, and the CS at mag 15.6 is too dim to see with this scope.
Very sparse, not concentrated. Brighter stars form a hexagon. Est class III 2 p.
Very sparse. 12 stars in a lance shape. Generally faint. Est class III 2 p.
Very faint. 5 dim stars stand out, and a slight sparkly general glow, a bit concentrated at the center. Est class II 2 m.
Fairly small, bright. Not too concentrated. 9 brightest stars in a rough egg shape. :) Est class III 3 p.
Somewhat dim, but rich cluster. Near a magnitude 10 star, S. Very nice. Est class II 2 m.
Line of 7 stars in a row, with two on the end. Zeta-tau is just to the west outside the view.
Very large and bright. Has an S shaped chain of stars. About 50 stars in the cluster. Est class III 3 m.
Extremely faint glow just brighter than the sky. Elongated, uniform brightness.
Very sparse, faint. Looks a little like a tennis racket. Est class II 2 p.
Very small, faint. Invisible except at high power. Only seen when jiggling the scope. Just a lighter patch, slightly concentrated. No stars resolved. Est class II 1 ?
Small, but fairly bright. Could see faintly at low power. About 7 brighter stars and haze of faint ones. Est class I 3 r.
Large, sparse, somewhat dim. Concentrated in the center. Like it! Est class I 1 p.
Faint sparkly glow concentrated at the center.
Very small and faint. See occasionally when bumping the scope. Core is round. Hints of larger structure outside the core, mottled and sparkly. Probably spiral.
Small, relatively bright. Core is bright and concentrated. Outer part slightly oval. Makes a cool "double double" effect with three other stars. :)
Very faint. See 50% of the time with averted vision. Elongated, small.
Very faint, slight sparkly glow next to a star. Not much brighter at the core.
Not seen at less than 250x. Unfiltered, see a faint dot with averted vision. With a UHC filter, somewhat brighter and a halo appears around the dot. still averted vision only.
At 141x, appears star-like with direct vision. At 250x, still star-like. Adding a UHC filter brightens it considerably. Hints of a faint ring around the center?

Very bright. Seen even at 40x as non-stellar. At 250x, see CS and a brighter circle around it, then a fainter disc around that. With UHC, has the odd effect of being brighter with averted vision, but dimmer with direct. Not much more detail seen. Upping the magnification to 321x (no filter) gives the best view. CS visible barely with direct vision.
Detected at 141x with no filter, averted vision. At 250x, see a faint two-lobed blob. UHC filter brings this out considerably. See two brighter dots within a larger circle. No CS seen.

Probably spent 40 minutes looking at this with different powers and filters. Invisible at high power with any filter (or none).  Only seen at 94x with an OIII filter. Occasionally see very faint nebulosity near a star. Brightest near the star to the west and north, sometimes seems to extend even more faintly towards the west.
Very faint, only visible at highest power. Soft, rich. Somewhat concentrated. Only some stars seen; rest create a speckled patch. Est class II 1 r.
At 250x, no filter, see a faint ring with averted vision, centered on a brighter mag 11 star. Adding UHC filter brings this out quite a bit, still only averted vision but much easier to see.
Bright, fairly large. Big variation in star magnitudes. Maybe 80-100 stars. Est class II 3 m.
Difficult to find and see. Invisible except with OIII filter. Then only an extremely faint glow. No CS or other details seen.
Extremely faint, just a soft glow. No bright core. Fairly small.
3166 on the W side. Oval. Core is bright. Pretty easy to see. 3169 is near the center. Smaller and dimmer, less concentrated, more uniform.
Small, faint. Easiest to see when moving the scope. Core not especially bright, fairly uniform.
Very faint. Moderately large. Core is only slight brighter.

Just a faint, slightly fuzzy point that flickers at the edge of detectability. See about 20% of the time. (The star A is magnitude 8 and can be held in the view with averted vision.) Not able to see here as a double, though it should be splittable. Just a bit too dim to see the components clearly.
Very large. Stars bright. Lots of double/multiple stars. Slightly concentrated. About 70 stars. Est class II 2 m.
Large cluster, stars somewhat dim. About 70 stars. Very spread out, but strong concentration at the center. Est class I 2 m.
Appears as faint nebulosity around a star. Elongated a little.
Very big, long. White wall, appears rounded and bumpy; uneven.
Looks like the Mario Yoshi dinosaur! Large, very bright. Double star near the center of the cluster. :) Est class II 3 m.
Round, big. Walls are raised and rough. See roughness in the center of the crater.

Invisible at lower power, and at 188x without a filter. A UHC filter brings it out just enough that I thought I could detect it. OIII darkens the sky enough that it's only "very faint" with averted vision. Appears as a soft gray circle. No detail or central star. In a nice asterism of a triangle of stars.
Large. Flat bottom. Incomplete walls. Small mountain in the middle. To the S, two lines of several craters. To the N is Hesiodus, which looks connected to Pitatus through a small channel.
Large. Two prominent craters near the N side. Interior is rough. Very cool to see with this phase and favorable libration.
Football-shaped with a small tail. Brighter spot within Oceanus Procellarum. Looks flat. Reiner is round, smooth. Looks like it has a faint bump in the middle.

At 141x, no filter, can see as a very faint fuzzy disc, fairly large, with averted vision. Adding UHC filter brightens this considerably, making it direct vision. No CS seen. With OIII filter, appears more solid. Dimmer, but improved contrast. Texture seems slightly mottled.
3729: faint. Appears as nebulosity around a star (but off to the side). 3718: Very faint, small, round. Think this is only the core, as it should be larger and elongated.
Faint, round. Slightly sparkly. Core is small and a little brighter with averted vision.
Very faint soft glow. Not too concentrated in the center.
M96: fairly bright. Elliptical. Core is very bright. M 95: smaller, fainter. A little difficult to see. Core is round and brighter. Both galaxies require averted vision to see.
Extremely faint. Barely detected. See 25% of the time as a small soft glow. Core not brighter.

Bright fuzzy star at 40x. At 141x, very bright, obvious spot. Can't see CS. At 250x, bright gray patch, soft fuzzy edges. UHC really brings out, see a slight ring structure and with averted vision, the CS.
Bright white circular ring, slightly wider on one side. Lighter gray interior. Three prominent lunar rays coming off it.
Somewhat irregular soft bump in a C-shape. Another smaller bump off to the SW and a small white crater to the S.
P.P.: Darker region W of Archimedes. Contains a dark dash-shaped and M-shaped regions. M.A.: lots of white spots and some small shadows; brighter than the surrounding area.

At 141x, unfiltered: see a brighter patch in the sky, large and amorphous, hard to see where it ends. UHC view is similar.  At 94x, using OIII, see a very faint glow, but more clearly defined. At this point, suspect the views at 141x were of a passing cloud.
Primary bright gold, secondary blue. Bright, wide double. :)
Triple is easily split at 40x. A brighter, and B,C similar magnitude, maybe C slightly brighter.
Stars easily split at 40x, but C is faint, need 141x to see with averted vision.
A's name is "Intercrus"; I find it surprising that a star this dim (mag 5.4) has a name!  A has a gold color, B and C white. B-C-A make 3 corners of an approximate square.

At 141x, no filter, appears star-like (or only see CS). Seen with direct vision.  UHC: brings this out a bit, now is brighter than nearby stars. At 250x+UHC, core seems disc-like and possibly hints of a ring structure.
Small, round, faint. Core is slightly brighter. Averted vision only.
Round, faint. Sparkly appearance. Center is brighter.
Elongated in NW-SE direction. Faint. Core is brighter. Easiest to see when moving the scope.
Diffuse. Core is a little brighter. ore area is circular.
Soft round glow. Center not particularly bright.

M86: bright, elliptical, bright core. M 84: very similar to M 86, core almost stellar. 4388: Quite faint, not too concentrated, elongated. 4438: Small and faint, somewhat concentrated. 4435: Small, faint, but core is brighter and more concentrated than 4438.
Medium large, fairly faint, slightly concentrated. Oval shaped, diffuse.
Faint and diffuse.
Very small and faint. Only apparent when moving the scope, else it blends into the background.

Mercury is star-like. Cool to see the star in the Pleiades appear as dusk falls - numbers indicate order in which they appeared.  Clouds over 50%-90% of the sky but amazingly this part of the sky stayed mostly clear. 9:06: can see Mercury naked eye (first time!), about 10 degrees above the horizon, WNW.  9:28: faintest hints of M 45 with averted vision naked eye.
Has two small mountains in the middle, next to 4 craterlets making a kite-shaped formation. Bottom is flat, walls are mountainous and uneven.

Difficult to draw. Peak on left is bright white: the tip of Mons Hadley, which has two additional smaller peaks. To the right is Mons Hadley Delta, with a curved shadow. At the base of the mountain is the site of the Apollo 15 mission. The Apollo 15 mission (on the moon July 30, 1971) was to study the Hadly-Apienne region.  It was the first of the Apollo "J" missions capable of a longer stay time on the moon and greater surface mobility.  It set several new records for crewed spaceflight: heaviest payload in a lunar orbit (about 107,000 pounds), maximum radial distance traveled on the lunar surface away from the spacecraft (about 17.5 miles), and longest total of duration for lunar surface EVAs (18 hours, 37 minutes).

Manilus: odd shadow - D-shaped, but not 1/2 of the crater. Crater has a bump in the middle, looks bowl-shaped, and has a terrace on part of one wall. Rima Hyginus: long, thin. Slight curvy. Has a dark line with a bright white just adjacent to it. Goes through a small crater, Hyginus. Boscovich: not circular. Elongated, narrow, shallow. Slightly darker interior. Nearby are darker gray areas, like low-contrast hills.
Faint, slightly brighter than the background sky. Just a blur, no stars resolved.
Fairly bright, sparkly. One brighter star, rest seen with averted vision. Can see individual stars flicker, but can't quite resolve the butterfly shape, though it is wider than tall.
Wow! Very big, very bright. Great open cluster. Resolve about 10 stars, seems somewhat concentrated at the center.
Extremely faint. Blinks in and out with averted vision. Small, slightly lighter patch. Near two (wide) double stars.
Very faint, concentrated. Sometimes seems star-like. Only see with averted vision.
Large round haze. Slightly brighter in the middle. Uneven texture.
M101: very large, bright, round. Core is a little brighter, and looks sparkly. NGC 5474: smaller, much fainter, core not much brighter.
Almost invisible with direct vision, but bright with averted. Mottled appearance, maybe a few stars resolved. Est class VII.
Actually easy with these dark skies. Seen at low power. Elongated. faint, almost transparent glow. Core slightly brighter. Many stars not shown.
Small. Fairly bright core. Maybe resolve some dimmer stars at the edge with averted vision. Est class V. Lots of field stars not shown.
Next to a double triangle asterism. Medium size, somewhat diffuse, not too bright. No stars resolved. Est class IX.
At low power, see a small bright patch, with some stars. At medium power, see a faint haze at the center. Est class II 3 p.
Soft fuzzy ball. No stars resolved. Est class VII.
Somewhat concentrated area, lots of background stars. Cluster has about 30 stars. Rough triangle shape. Nebulosity near the center. This reminds me of M11 or NGC 7789. :) Est class IV 2 p.
6522: fairly bright, could see at low power. Hints of mottled texture with averted vision. Est class IV. 6528: slightly smaller, not too bright. Seems concentrated at the center. Est class III.
Seen at low power. Somewhat diffuse, no stars resolved. Medium bright. Est class VIII.
Not seen at low power, but still pretty obvious at 141x. Faint smudge, uneven brightness. In the middle of a chain of stars. Est class X.
Quite bright, seen at low power. No stars resolved. Center is concentrated. Est class II.
Medium bright. Saw at low power. Soft and diffuse. No stars resolved. Est class X.
Somewhat faint. Detected at low power, though. Best seen with averted vision. Just a mottled gray patch. Est class II 2 r.
Can see some faculae near the spots near the edge.
Medium dim fuzz ball. Hints of speckling.
Very faint, blinks in and out with averted vision and moving the binoculars. Small. Center is slightly brighter. No stars resolved.
Very bright, easy to see nebulosity. Can find this just panning around the area. Can see about 6 stars in a row and 3 spots of nebulosity. One of my favorite Messiers.
Faint glowing patch. Center is not much brighter. Next to a fairly bright star (mag 6.5).
Quite bright, easy to see. Center is concentrated. Bright star to the E is Kaus Borealis.
Very sparse, not concentrated. Stars not too bright. Est class III 1 p.
Has a nice propeller shape. One bright star in the middle. :) Est class I 3 p.
Small and very faint. Two brighter stars, about 10 dim ones, and a few more at the limit of detection. Est class II 2 p.
Only one sunspot visible.
M 13: bright and sparkly. Tons of small stars resolved. Glow extends far from the center of the cluster. 6207 (marked): Quite faint. Elongated. Core is a bit brighter and more circular.
Faint stars. Not concentrated. About 30 stars. Est class III 2 p.

M8: With no filter, just a small bright patch. UHC brings this out a lot, and OIII slightly more, so it's quite bright. Probably the best view of this I've had in Bellevue. 6530: Bright and sparkly. Est class II 2 p.
Primary is gold and very bright. Secondary is bluish and very dim. Secondary should be splittable, but seeing is not good enough tonight.

Barely visible as a star with averted vision. Adding a UHC filter brings this out some, still averted vision, but brighter and easier. OIII filter brings this out even more; it now appears equally bright as the star next to it.

At 141x, invisible with no filter. Adding a UHC, I see a very faint haze, maybe with a CS. OIII filter is similar. Upping the magnification to 188x + UHC makes this easier.  Small, faint, star-like, averted vision only.

Unfiltered, I see the PN, but don't realize it; it looks like any other very faint star. Adding the UHC brightens it considerably. Appears star-like, only seen with averted vision, and blinks out with direct vision.
Very big and bright. Seen in the finderscope. About 50 stars, concentrated at the center. Bright pair of stars at the center. :) Est class I 3 m.

At 141x, invisible with no filter. A UHC filter shows a faint star-like point with averted vision. An OIII filter darkens everything too much. Increasing magnitude (with UHC filter) helps a little. On the border of a square asterism.
Two groups of spots, three each. Can see small penumbra on the largest spot in the middle. See another small spot to the W.
Really nice display of spots today. 4 of the largest spots have visible penumbra, and the topmost spot has little faint chains coming off it!

Two pairs of sunspots with chains between them. One on the S side is very pronounced, with 7-8 spots. Additionally, 3 more smaller isolated spots; can see faculae around the one on the SE edge.  Also took a closer view at 80x of the prominent chain.
A, B close and about equally bright. C is much farther and fainter. Very cute.
A, B white, quite close. Just barely cleanly split at 141x. C is faint.
A, B bright, not split most of the time. Can sometimes see them partially split in moments of steadier seeing. C is dimmer, D even fainter, maybe magnitude 13. Many other stars in the field.
Primary is bright gold. B, C fainter, but widely split. Large spread in magnitudes.
Large sunspot group has a cool thin filament connecting the two subgroups. See about 19 individual spots! Several have distinct penumbras.
A, B fairly close, white and same magnitude. C a bit dimmer. All stars are in a straight line! Split (barely) at low power (40x). About 1 star-width between A and B.
A is bright, mag 6.7. B is faint, mag 10. C very faint, and pretty close to A; hard to see, need averted vision.

Seen at 94x with averted vision, no filter. Appears stellar. A bit easier at 188x, still mostly averted vision, as it tends to blink out with direct. UHC brightens this somewhat. Part of a 6-point dolphin asterism.
Three large groups of spots, plus two near the East limb.

Invisible without a filter. At 141x with UHC see a faint gray patch. Increasing magnification actually makes this harder to see. Lowering to 94x+OIII brings this out a bit more. Can see a faint ring structure. Still averted vision only. No CS.
Six groups of spots visible. The one in the center-south has a spiral of smaller spots coming out.
5 groups of spots. Two brightest spots have visible penumbras. 16 total spots visible.

Appears stellar at all magnifications from 141x to 321x. UHC and OIII filters have no effect. Believe the PN is behind a star (or CS is bright and the rest of the nebula is dim). Many other field stars not drawn. When looking directly at the star, can see a small faint diffraction ring (other stars with similar magnitude show this, too). With averted vision, the area around the star looks a little brighter. While I also see this with some other stars (likely diffraction due to my curved spider vanes) this star shows it a bit more than the others. So maybe I am seeing the PN.  Note that B+30 3639 is an alternate name of the variable star V1966 Cyg; The PN is actually ARO 11 or PK 064+05.1.
At 141x unfiltered, appears star-like. Adding UHC brightens this considerably. At 250x, sill stellar with UHC. Trying OIII looks very bright! All other stars mostly disappear.

Looks stellar at lower power (141x). At 188x, could see hints that the PN was not stellar. Adding UHC shows a tiny disc, no detail. Increasing mag to 321x unfiltered shows the best view. Can see barely with direct vision. Bright center, see CS with averted vision, then a lighter disk on the outside.
At 141x, easily seen gray disc (averted vision only). Responds well to both UHC and OIII filters. At 188x, see a flat disc, but sometimes see hints of some structure (a ring? not sure) No CS.

Not seen at 141x, either unfiltered nor with UHC. See a faint hint of a star in the right spot at 250x (no filter). 321x makes it a little easier, (still faint, stellar), and adding a UHC confirms it by brightening it a little bit.
Invisible without a filter. UCH reveals a faint gray patch. Somewhat amorphous. No CS seen. Averted vision only. Best seen when I nudge the scope.
Wow. Bright, fairly rich cluster. Brightest stars like on an annulus (that is, the center has relatively few stars). Like it! Est class II 2 m.
At 188x, unfiltered, appears star-like, with direct vision. UHC brightens it considerably. Increasing mag to 321x + a UHC reveals a very small bright disc.
About 10 stars. Large magnitude difference. 5 fairly bright stars. Est class II 3 p.
Lots of smaller spots today. 8 roughly in a line. Two largest spots have penumbras.
The coathanger is bright and fun. Correctly oriented. NGC 6802 is quite faint and small, a gray patch that I see occasionally with averted vision. Bumping the scope helps.
Spot on the W limb ha faculae. Also seems inset a little bit. Other bright spots have small penumbras. Also a small slightly denser patch near the center.
M71: diffuse, some speckling like a thin cotton ball, maybe class X. H20: 2 bright stars, about 10 fainter ones. Cluster is elongated.  Est class III 2 p.

Not seen without a filter. At 141x+UHC, see a faint glow near 3 stars with averted vision. Similar, but darker with an OIII. At 250x + UHC see a soft dot clearly with averted vision. No CS, but center is brighter, edges slightly fuzzy.

Not seen without a filter. At 141x, adding UHC reveals the faintest hint of a glow at  the edge of detection. With OIII this brightens considerably. Still averted vision only. No CS. Soft, med size gray patch. A little amorphous, but no structure seen.
Seen at 141x. Appears stellar with averted vision. At 250x, still stellar, averted vision. Adding UHC brightens this a bit to confirm which dot is the PN.

Quite near V Aql, which has a great saturated orange color. See at 141x with averted vision as a fairly bright, small fuzzy dot (no filter). At 250x, almost direct vision. Center is brighter, and outside fainter like an unresolved globular.  UHC and OIII both brighten the outside; prefer unfiltered view. At 321x, is a soft cotton ball, fuzzy edges, direct vision. Hints of a CS sometimes. :)
Stellar at 141x, averted vision. Still stellar at 250x. But responds well to a UHC filter, so I can confirm it. Averted vision only.
Two bright spots. Biggest one has penumbra 3 other small spots in 2 groups.

At 141x, no filter, see a bright soft dot, right next to a star. Blinks out with direct vision. At 321x, no filter, see medium bright fuzzy ball. Faint with direct vision. With averted vision, I can see a faint ring, and (I think) a CS. UHC makes the PN bigger and brighter, but details are harder to see. Like unfiltered better.

Big and bright. Can see in finderscope (small and faint with averted vision). At 188x, nicely framed in the view at the center of a square of stars. Large and diffuse. Two lobes in a fat dumbbell shape. Direct vision, no CS. Adding UHC brightens the PN, showing an apple-core center in an oval outside. OIII: darker, but can see some structure: faint filaments coming out from the apple core. Bit of a toss up whether UHC or OIII is better here. My wife's comment: "Oh,that's amazing! No wonder you spend hours looking at the stars!"
Two spots visible. Larger one has a penumbra. After switching to higher power and back, can see one more faintly on the west limb.
Very large, fairly bright. Lots of stars. Mostly within a pentagon of brighter stars. Est class II 2 m.
Large. Sparse. Fairly bright. A little hard to realize is a cluster. Described as an (upside down) eagle, which seems accurate. :) Est class II 3 p.

At 141x, invisible without a filter. See a small glow with averted vision with a UHC. Even brighter with an OIII. Increasing magnification helps a bit, too. Round, flat fuzzy disc. No CS or other details. Averted vision only.
16 Cyg: bright wide double. about equal magnitudes. 6826: fain with direct vision, very bright disc with averted vision. Slightly brighter in the center.
About 25 stars. Also known as the toadstool or mushroom asterism, which it roughly resembles. Est class III 2 p.

Invisible without filter, not seen with UHC either. Extremely faint glow at 171x, slightly easier to see at 188x, still very difficult, near limit of detection. No CS seen. Helps to tap the scope. Going back to UHC at 188x, can actually see it a little more easily. Right next to a faint star.
Three sunspots in two groups.
No nebulosity seen except with an OIII filter, then very faint. Cluster is big and bright, with 7-8 brighter stars in a spiral. Just under 50 stars total. Est class III 3 p.
Somewhat small, but bright. About 20 stars. Est class II 2 p.
Small, sparse, and faint. Near a brighter mag 9 star.
4 stars in a tight pattern, two more farther away. Est class I 1 p. Stars (which are mag 10-12) are all very faint due to the poor sky conditions.
5 sunspots in 2 groups.
3 bright stars, maybe 30 fainter ones. Est class III 2 p.
At 141x, no filter: invisible. Also not seen with UHC and OIII.  At 250x and UHC can see a very faint glow with averted vision. No CS seen.

Found the trapezoid pointer asterism, and see a general blob at the correct location; can't resolve PN or nearby stars. Flashing an OIII filter darkens everything significantly; can only see the core of M15 and the bright star.
Faint, very sparse. Est class III 2 p. Many other field stars not drawn.
7723: faint, core not very bright. Diffuse, a little difficult. 7727: faint, but bright core, almost stellar.  Cool small cluster in the NW field of view.
One chain with seven spots. Largest spot has a penumbra.

Seen at 94x, unfiltered, with averted vision: a med bright small fuzzy ball, brighter in the center.  At 250x larger, but still averted vision. A UHC brings this out well, OIII even more but generally too dark. With UHC, has a general ring structure, but is brighter on the N side - almost a blob there - slightly brighter on the S, and dimmer on the E side. Right next to a double star. No CS seen. Very cool.
Chain of 5 spots and a new spot on the E side with faculae.
6 fairly bright spots. Can see faint faculae for the spot on the E side, and a penumbra for the spot on the E middle.
Very large faint glow. Irregular shape. Also a bright star cluster. Best view so far from Bellevue. Helps to nudge the scope to see the extent of the nebulosity.

Spent about 45 minutes attempting to see Pease 1. This time I have my equatorial platform, which helps substantially. Stayed completely hooded, and successfully got the blinking technique down.
