UHC filter may work better since the view is not quite so dim. Unfortunately, can't detect any brightening yet. But can see the locating asterisms and a small dot where the PN should be.
Small, isolated mountain in Mare Imbrium. Bright white. Has two peaks.
A is a beautiful light coppery orange. B is much dimmer, almost disappears with direct vision. C about the same magnitude as B. :)
AB - slight yellow color, bright. These are separated by 0.6"; can't see any split tonight. C is fairly bright, D faint.
A bright. B, C are very faint, hard to see. B, A, C are all in a line with two other stars. At 250x, B and C are easy to see, and a very wide split from A.
Super bright, wide split. Easy in binoculars or finderscope. Other components fainter, but still seen in lower power view.
Small. Very faint. Resolve a few stars, but the rest are just a haze. Est class II 1 m.  Difficult.
Very sparse. Some stars very faint. Hard to tell where the cluster is; circle marked from SkySafari. Est class III 3 p. Looked up afterwards - this is classified as a star, not a cluster?!
3 brighter stars and a few fainter ones. Est class III 2 p.
Nebulosity near a star toward the S and SW. Careful averted vision reveals 4 stars in a U shape.  Est class I 2 p.
Saturn has a pale brown stripe on the N side. Rings go in front of Saturn on the S (up) side. Can see 6 moons, in order of brightness: Titan, Iapetus, Rhea, Dione, Tethys, Enceladus.
6 spots, two quite large and dark with penumbrae. All spots near the edges have faculae. Faint one on the E side has a long one that snakes to the edge.
5 spots. 3 brightest have small penumbrae.
3 bright spots, 7 fainter ones.
16 sunspots in 6 groups! Pretty nice display.  Also looked at E cluster at 50x.
Bright, wide splits. Easily seen at 141x. A, C very bright and orange. B is dim, maybe a reddish hue. D is dimmest.
A, B equal magnitude. Very tight split (0.9"). However just barely spit cleanly. C, D  wide, bright, easy at med power. :)
A (NV Peg) is pale orange. B is dim. C is very faint.
20 sunspots in 4 groups. Large penumbra on the S cluster, and faculae seen on the W cluster.

Saturn was at opposition yesterday. Rings are possibly brighter than usual? Hard to tell. Red fringe on the top, blue on the bottom (like a refractor) due to atmospheric refraction. One band toward the N side, slightly darker brown. Cassini Division faintly seen as a darker color through the rings. See shadow of Saturn on the rings, and sometimes the shadow of the rings on Saturn.

Detected at 141x with averted vision. Looks like a fuzzy star. At 250x, is brighter but still averted vision only. Center is almost stellar, and can see a faint gray haze around it. Responds some to UHC and quite a bit to an OIII filter, though the latter darkens the view too much. OIII reveals that the bright cluster is the PN and not a CS.

Seen at 141x as stellar, with averted vision. Blinks out with direct vision, while nearby stars do not. Still stellar at 321x; still only averted vision. Responds well to a UHC filter; appears brighter than the star next to it.
At 141x, invisible without a filter. Using a UHC, see a very faint small glow. OIII filter brightens this more. At 188x + OIII, appears as a faint gray disc. No CS or detail. Still rather faint.
20 sunspots in 3 groups. Group towards the left has fancy structure (13 spots)!
A is V381 Cep. Bright, pale tangerine orange, obvious at low power. B is faint, very near A, resolved at 141x. D is brighter than B.
8 brighter stars, and a specking of many faint ones. Est class III 3 m.
Bright star in the center is zeta-Cep. Has a nice orange color. Looks like a crossbow!  Easy to find and see. :)
Difficult. Third attempt. Faint fuzzy patch, a few stars resolved. Near a brighter star (mag 12) in the center of the view. Est class II 2 p.

Very faint, concentrated at the center. Required a minute or two of study before I could see this. Stars are elusive; I can't hold them in vision, they blink in and out. Hard to draw accurately. Est class I 2 p.
Very near NGC 7510; could see them both in the view at 141x. K19 is sparse, wide variety of magnitudes, about 15 stars. Est class III 3 p.
Large, diffuse. Seen faintly at low power. Oval shaped. Blends into the background.  First time seen in Bellevue.

Very difficult, extremely faint. At 250x, see a lighter patch occasionally when moving the scope. Increasing the magnitude to 321x help; see a stellar core with slight nebulosity, still very hard to see.
Faint nebulosity around a sparse cluster of stars. Nebulosity disappears without the UHC filter.
Seen as a smudge in the finderscope. Low power reveals a small hat-shaped asterism of stars. At 188x, see 8 bright stars and 15-20 very dim ones. Est class II 3 p.
Very large and very bright. General triangle shape. About 40 stars. Est class III 3 p.
Very faint lighter patch. Slightly concentrated towards the center. No tail, nucleus seen.
Very faint blur, seems slightly glittery. Best seen when moving the scope. No tail visible. Difficult.
Faint glow around two stars. Best seen without a filter. Part of a 6-star asterism. Stars are bright, seen faintly at low power.

7245: Medium size. Stars are moderately faint, sparse, spread out. Est class III 1 p. K9: very small and faint. Can't resolve stars clearly; sort of a misty slightly-sparkly patch. Concentrated. Est class I 2 m.

At 188x, no filter: invisible. Responds a little to a UHC filter; see some faint nebulosity around a star. Adding OIII filter is even better. See a nice ring around the star. CS is bright, can see with direct vision. PN requires averted vision. Increasing power makes the view too dim. :)
Extremely faint glow. Very small. No stars resolved, but slight speckled appearance. Somewhat concentrated. Est class II 2 m.  Star marked M is magnitude 14.1, near edge of detection.

4 in the view! 7788: big, bright, sparse. Est class III 2 p. 7790: small glow with 5 stars resolved. Fr1: see 3 stars clearly, maybe 5 with careful averted vision. Slight brightness probably from a few other fainter unresolved stars. Ha21: Med size, very sparse. See 5 faint stars in the shape of a Z.
A is vibrant gold, B is a little dimmer and gray-blue. C is white. Great color contrast! Love it! :)

Seen at 188x with averted vision; blinks out with direct vision. Appears stellar. Responds well to a UHC filter, and even more with OIII. Unfiltered, was dimmer than nearby star N, now is brighter. Always just stellar.

At 188x, invisible without a filter and with UHC. Faint hint of a glow with OIII. At 250x, only seen with UHC; invisible unfiltered and too dark with OIII. Located towards one side of a rhombus of stars. Can see a faint CS with averted vision, and when moving the scope, a faint glow around it. No detail.
Kappa And is brilliant white. Other stars are faint.
A is pale yellow-gold, bright. B is slightly dimmer, light blue. Nice colors!
About 1 degree N of Lambda-And. Diamond-shape formed from about 15 stars. Visible at low power (38x).
A bright; B, C are dim and about similar magnitude. All stars are white.

Ganymede eclipse. Jupiter a bright white disc, no detail. Ganymede nearly touching Jupiter. Starting around 10:58, it starts getting dimmer. By 11:01:00, was quite dim, only seen with averted vision, and by 11:01:40 it had completely disappeared. Other moon distances marked in Jupiter-widths.
At this power, Saturn is mostly an elongated oval, very small. Careful examination shows the shape of the planet + rings (circle + ellipse). Cannot see the space between the rings and the planet.

See 4 stars in a trapezoid. Hints of some fainter ones (6-7 total in the asterism). Need mag 5 skies to see all the other faint stars in the chain. A bit underwhelming. Bright 2 stars are 98, 99 Aqr, easy to find and see.
About 12 brighter stars, maybe another 10 faint ones (say mag 12-13). Small concentrated, fairly bright seen as a slight blur at 40x. Est class II 2 p.
Fairly large and sparse. Seen faintly at low power (40x). Encircled on the E side by an arc of brighter stars. Est class IV 1 p.

Seen very faintly as a small lighter patch at 40x (no filter). At 113x, no filter, can see 2 lobes, now easy to see with averted vision. At 188x, no filter can see the dumbbell shape with averted vision, and a nebulous glow with direct vision. UHC filter brings this out quite a bit, easier to see the shape. No CS seen. :)
Very faint and diffuse. Best seen when moving the scope.
Sparse, not too bright, some variety in brightnesses. Brighter stars form 3 crossed lines. Est class II 2 p.
Nebulosity around a star. No filter: invisible. UHC brightens so its pretty apparent with averted vision. Doesn't show well with OIII. Only 1 other star in the FOV.
Very large, complex shape. Some darker areas through the nebula. Can also the the Pelican nebula as well. Wow.
Seen as a small faint glow at 40x. At 250x, is a larger glow with a speckling of stars. Averted vision only; faint. Est class III 2 r.

Seen at 40x, no filter, as a large glow with faint thin ring on the outside. At 113x, glow is direct vision. Responds well to UHC; is a large bright disc. OIII: also bright but shows outer ring better. Think I can see faint CS. Very nice!
Seen at 40x. Fairly bright. Mottled texture - spiral arms? [Yes, is a spiral galaxy.] Core not too bright. Next to a mag 13.7 star.

Seen at 40x, no filter, as a glow around 3 stars. At 188x, unfiltered, see a faint diffuse glow with averted vision in a doughnut shape! UHC brings this out slightly; shape is more defined. CS is bright. See a ring, plus brighter towards the NW side. Interior is slightly brighter than backgrounds sky. Really amazing!
Seen faintly with averted vision at 40x, a small blur near a star. At 113x, see brighter core, and elongated outer part. Center of core looks stellar (but faint, like a mag 14 star).
Appears stellar at 40x. At 188x, fairly small, bright. Brighter core is nearly circular, edge is elongated.
Medium bright. Small, round. Core is brighter but not stellar.
1052: medium bright. core very bright, almost stellar. Small, slightly oval. 1042: faint, diffuse glow, not brighter at the core. Larger than 1052.
Small, bright, oval-shaped. Core slightly brighter. Faint spiral arms maybe. [Yes, is a spiral galaxy!]
Faint diffuse glow. Slightly brighter in the center.

Seen faintly at 40x as a small gray blur. At 113x, no filter, see with averted vision a faint glow, maybe in an annulus, around a bright central star. UHC brings this out some, but the shape still seems irregular. OIII brings this out a little more. PN is shaped like an ellipse, seems brighter along the N side. Neat.

1407 (E side): Quite bright. Core very bright almost stellar. 1400 (W side): Also bright, smaller than 1407. Is oval-shaped and has a stellar core. 1400 (N side): Very small and faint. A little difficult. Not concentrated.
Irregular gray patches surrounding a dark area. Not too bright. Unfiltered view is best; UHC and OIII don't help much.
Faint glow around 3 stars. Irregular shaped. Filters didn't help.
Bright, sparse. Seen at low power. One very bright star. About 20 stars. Est class II 3 p.
Very bright, sparse. Has a snail shape. About 30 star. Est class III 2 p.
141x, no filter: invisible. At 188x, no filter, invisible. With UHC, see a very faint soft glow with averted vision. Flat, no detail or CS.
Small, not too bright but seen at medium power. Poor-about 10 stars. 5 brightest stars form an arc. Est class III 2 p.
Not clearly resolved; see only a faint glow near 3 brighter stars. Can't estimate the class.
Invisible at lower power with any filter. At 188x, only seen with UHC filter. Very faint with averted vision. Appears as a tiny gray dot, sometimes just as a star. Maybe the CS?
Bright, sparse, pretty large. Has a general S shape. Reminds me of a snake eating an elephant (from the Little Prince). :) I like this cluster! Est class III 3 p.

At 113x, see a soft glow, slightly brighter in the center with averted vision. Adding a UHC filter brightens it quite a bit, though still averted vision only. At 188x + UHC, see a ring! Interior is brighter than the background field. No CS. Further magnification doesn't help. :)
Nice bright cluster. Large magnitude difference between stars. Marked star i pale orange. About 40 stars. Est class II 3 p.

Appears stellar with averted vision at 113x, and blinks out with direct vision (nearby stars do not!) At 188x, still stellar. UHC brings it out slightly; OIII filter brightens it quite a bit. In a small cluster of stars.
Main part of the cluster has a triangular shape. Fairly bright. Saw hints of it at 40x. :) Est class II 2 p.

Played around with this at 38x to 45x, with UHC and OIII filters (at 45x). Generally didn't see much. However sometimes a very large (about the size of the entire FOV) seemed slightly lighter, or more opaque than the nearby sky. Not too convinced. After a while, with the OIII filter, I saw a slightly brighter triangular patch, able to see this repeatedly.  This is the second closest PN to Earth, 400ly.
Small, rather faint cluster near a bright magnitude 6 star. Cluster has 3 brighter stars and about 15 very faint stars. Est class I 3 p.
Nebulosity around a star. Circular. Brighter in the center. Averted vision only. UHC filter bring this out a little. OIII is bad: too dark and doesn't show up.
No filter: don't see anything. UHC: some patchy nebulosity. OIII: nebulosity slightly more defined. Very large. Irregular shape. Only seen when moving the scope. Many more stars not drawn.

Only seen with UHC filter. Very faint, averted vision only. Very small gray disc; no features or CS seen. Can only see occasionally. Difficult. Only the brightest stars in the field drawn. Attempted this twice from Bellevue without success; requires a dark site.
Fuzzy oval slightly brighter at the core. Faint, seems transparent. Tried this twice without luck from Bellevue; requires dark skies.

2453: small, bright cluster behind a chain of stars. Est class I 2 p. 2452: seen without a filter with averted vision. Small gray circle, with hints of a ring structure, no CS seen. With UHC, appears more clear, can see a ring and CS in the middle.
Modestly large. A bit faint. Sparkly. Est class I 2 m.

Bright. About 20 stars, not concentrated. A bit hard to distinguish against the star field. Assuming that faint stars in the center belong to the background and are not part of the cluster; faint stars not drawn - there are lots of them! Has a hexagon shape. Est class IV 1 p.
Very faint. A little elongated. Center is slightly brighter. Surprisingly hard for a dark site.
2571: Quite bright. Concentrated. Has 3 very bright stars. Est class I 3 p. :) 2567: Dimmer, though still visible at low power. Diffuse, slightly larger than 2571. Est class II 2 m.
Fine sparkly patch of stars. Somewhat concentrated. Large variety of magnitudes. Est class II 3 m.
Large bright cluster. Visible through finderscope. General pentagon shape, cross with two chains of stars. Est class II 3 m.
Bright. Concentrated. Fairly large. About 40 stars. Stars are bright. Est class I 1 m.

Caught Ganymede as it was brightening; eclipse was supposed to start at 5:14.  Around 5:10 at first view, G was barely visible. By 5:11 it was dim but easy to see. By 5:15 it seems similar brightness to Europa. Jupiter shows no detail, just a bright white disc.
4 large groups of spots. One on the E side large with penumbra. Group on the N has almost 12 spots. About 39 spots total!
Large, bright. Lots of stars--like a mist. Very nice! Difficult to draw accurately. Bright star in the center is orangeish. Est class I 2 r.
At 113x, could clearly see a disc, pale green-blue. At 250x, seems whiter/grayer. Count not detect any of the moons; probably need somewhat darker skies and better seeing.
Long, thin cluster; almost seems like two clusters side by side. About 40 stars. :) Est class III 2 p.
DoDz 3: small, very poor. 10 stars. Brightest stars make an arc. Est class II 2 p. DoDz 4: slightly larger and brighter. Still very poor, around 12 stars. Est class II 3 p.  Two in the view!
Just North of M42. Fairly large, sparse. About 10 stars. Adding UHC filter reveals faint nebulosity around the brightest stars. Est class III 2 p.

Venus: almost full, gibbous. Looks round. Bright white, not detail. Red fringing at the top, blue at the bottom. Saturn: rings very flat. See shadow on the right side of the planet, and thin space between the planet and rings. Saturn is dim brown/yellow.

Sketched with charcoal. Albategnius: smooth, flat bottom, somewhat darker. Large peak in the middle. On the south side wall there's a large crater, Klein, that has a cool crescent inside breaking through the shadow. Hipparchus: flat bottom, lighter than Albategnius. Has some wrinkle ridges, and in the center a half-hidden crater with a darker bottom. South side rougher and mountainous.
Fairly bright, seen in the finderscope. Star-like nucleus, and a large circular haze around it. No tail seen.
Thick ridged mountainous walls. Large peak in the middle. One prominent craterlet.
1502: four bright stars, one a close double; a string of very faint stars going through it. KK: about 15-16 medium faint stars in a wavy line.

Seen at low power. At 113x, faint and fairly large. Diffuse. Adding UHC filter brings this out some. Hazy, nebulous. Center not too bright. No detail. OIII filter: maybe brings a little more contrast, but too dim. Sketched with white charcoal on black paper.
Deep, dark orange. Not too bright but very vibrant. Cool! Sketched with gel pens on black paper.
Seen at low power. Appears stellar at 113x. Adding UHC brightens this a bit and confirms it's a PN. Sketched with white charcoal and gel pens on black paper.
36 spots in 7 groups. Spots in the brightest 4 groups have clear penumbrae. Group on W side can see white faculae around it.
Can see E and F stars in the Trapezium during stiller moments. Orion nebula is bright. Can see it extend faintly to the edge of the FOV. Can see mottled filaments with averted vision.
Nice 37 upside down! Cluster has 15 stars. Est class II 2 p. Bright and fun!
NGC 2175: winding snaky chain of stars, one bright, the rest dimmer.  NGC 2174: faint nebulosity over the whole area, brought out some with UHC filter. Roughly hourglass shape.
Comet-like. Bright point with a triangular tail coming off it. Very unusual. UHC filter doesn't help.
Large, bright. Looks like an outline of a Christmas tree. The bright star is the trunk. Est class III 3 p. About 30 stars.
Very large and bright. Bright orange star near the center (marked). Cluster has a general triangular shape, like a bird spreading its wings. Est class II 2 m.
Extremely faint without filter. UHC brings this out a bit. Faint, irregular shaped glow. Mostly see when moving the scope.
A: very bright, B: faint, C: difficult, averted vision only.  Part of NGC 1980
A: dim, B: harder, c: requires averted vision, similar mag to B.
No filter: bright round. Center very bright. See a central star. Looks like a class VI globular. Adding UHC filter brightens the outer part forming a gray annulus.
Faint transparent glow. Best seen when moving the scope. Central part slightly brighter.
Fairly bright. Core is brighter. See 2 spiral arms, I think. Like it! :)
Resolves into two galaxies. Brighter one, 4038, has a prominent C shape. The other, 4039, is fainter and has an S shape. Very cool.
Bright. Seen at low power. Thin and elongated.
Fairly bright. Core is only slightly brighter.
Somewhat faint, though seen at low power. Round. Core not bright. Slightly mottled. Spiral? Outside fuzzy, and fades into the background.
Moderately faint. Appears transparent, as an elliptical glow. Several stars in front of the galaxy.
4536: faint, center is brighter, the very core is stellar. Elongated. 4527: brighter, slightly larger. Elliptical, stellar core.
Long and thin. Somewhat faint. Core not very bright.
Faint glow. Round, diffuse. Have to know where to look to see this, but still able to see at low power. Last Herschel 400 object!

M65: stellar core, center of galaxy is very bright. Center seems turned at an angle compared to the outer part. M66: bigger than M65, also very bright. Core bright but not quite stellar. 3623: long and thin. Core not especially bright.
Great starhop here through Stargate and Jaws asterisms. M104: can see a big dust lane across the galaxy for the first time! Appears as a flat edge. Amazing!
Big. Long and thin. Diffuse, uniform brightness.  Bright foreground star near the center.
4567/4568: very similar looking. Centers are brighter but not stellar. Large haze surrounding the centers, overlapping. 4564: small, bright. Stellar core

Odd effect seeing so many galaxies at once. It feels like I'm out of focus, or the seeing is abysmal. M84/M86 are big and bright, with stellar cores. 4402 and 4388 elongated. 4435 and 4438 are "The Eyes"; about the same total brightness, but 4435 is more concentrated. 4413: small and very faint. 4387: haze around some faint stars.
Big, bright, very thin and long. Bright core with a bulge, and a thin dust lane. Wow!
Somewhat faint. The two galaxies have a distorted L shape. Best seen when moving the scope. 4656 has a hook? [yes!] and mottled texture. 4657 is the bottom of the L.
Simply amazing! Never seen so much detail on spiral arms! Bridge between the galaxies is difficult; very faint with averted vision.
About 57 in 4 groups. Nice display with clear umbrae, penumbrae, and faculae (indicated by gray outlines).

Prominent multi-peak mountain in the center. Bottom is flat and smooth. Walls are rocky, and on the East (sun illuminated) side, very rough. Rim has white highlights and black shadows. Sketched with charcoal - very difficult!

M101: quite faint. Round, slightly glittery. Faintest hint of a spiral arm on the N side.  SN: is a bright star. Location confirmed afterwards. Based on other stars' magnitudes (marked), estimate the SN magnitude to be about 11.

Montes Apenninus: look tall, large, rocky. Rough to the South. Mare Vaporum: has a dark, rough, depressed area. Sinus Aestuum: dark floor. Sinus Medii: smooth gradation from lighter to darker. Sketched with white conte crayon on black paper.

Davy has flat bottom, ridged walls. Davy C is prominent, bowl shaped. Davy Y is a large crater area. Bounded by craters/mountains to the NW and hills/hints of craters on other sides. Can see 4 tiny craterlets pop in and out of visibility in moments of good seeing.
Large group of sunspots. No granulation visible or penumbral grain. Wilson effect not seen (though the group is near the edge). McIntosh sunspot classification Fac.
Very bright, seen in finderscope. Lots of stars resolved. One bright star to the SW. Very beautiful. Sketched with Mellish technique: black paper, white pastel, colored pencil, and gel pen.

Star-like at low power. Appears fuzzy at 113x. Tried UHC filter, brightens a bit, but is still a bright white oval. No CS or internal details. Best view is highest power with no filter. See a bright white oval, with a faint halo around it.

Super large and bright. Lots of stars resolved, appears loos at the outside. See several chains of stars, as well as a clear view of dust lanes. Sketched with Mellish technique; black paper, white pastel, white colored pencil, and white gel pen.
Very faint gray patch near a star. Hints of a tail toward the SW. Best seen when moving the scope.

Large, bright. Center is concentrated, maybe class III. Can't increase magnification more without everything becoming shimmering and blurry. Maybe 50 brighter stars, and a mist of smaller ones near the core. Straight chain of stars in the center and more arcing chains on the outside.
M4: bright, still see some stars resolved. Dense core. 6144: faint gray patch, smaller. Not concentrated, perhaps class X. Only seen with averted vision. Antares is just out of the view.

Unfiltered, can see a general glow with direct vision, and with averted vision , clear 3-way dust lanes. UHC brings this out a bit, as well as other nebulosity to the N. Bright, generally circular, with a bright star in the center (hints of a double star, but seeing is bad), and obvious Y shaped dust lanes. Trying OIII filter, also pretty well defined, but a bit darker. UHC filter is better.  Wow! Sketched on black paper with conte crayon and gel pen.

6520: bright, maybe 6-9 bright stars (are they foreground or in the cluster?) and a concentrated bright circular patch. B86: to the West of 6520 see a clear dark black patch; rest of view is slightly gray. Very cool. First time seeing a DN! Tons of stars in the view, only the brightest sketched.
General swan shape; smaller 2-shaped head and long bright, diffuse body. Tons of stars in the view! See dark band across the top of the "back", and some mottling in the texture.
Only nebulosity is a small faint glow by a cluster of stars. Open cluster has about 50 stars in two sub-clusters.
Very rich cluster. One bright star. See darker patches. All stars appear resolved with averted vision, but unless looking closely, the stars appear as nebulous clouds. Very hard to draw!
Near opposition; the shadow appears equal on both sides. Can only barely make out the Cassini division. See a darker band on the N side.

Star-like at low power (40x). At 113x, small, slightly fuzzy. At 250x is elliptical in shape and has a hint of green color. Adding UHC filter makes this bigger and brighter but adds no detail. No CS seen.
Can detect elongation of the close doubles at 65x. Can split them cleanly at 113x. Best view at 250x. Very pretty. :)
Centered in a wide square of stars. Never noticed this before.  Primary is brilliant gold, secondary is pale deep blue.
Bright white stars. Clear coathanger shape.
Some nebulosity without a filter, but with UHC, get a large circular clout with prominent dust lanes. Spectacular!  Sketched on black paper with conte crayon and gel pen.
Very bright, solid disc. No CS seen. Filters don't help much. Center of the disc seems slightly shimmery with averted vision -- maybe a ring structure?
See very faint nebulosity without a filter; adding UHC helps a lot, and OIII adds slightly more detail. Egg-shaped nebula with sharper outline on N side. Very nice! C-shaped.
Very faint, diffuse glow. No detail.
Round, bright, slightly fuzzy ball. Hints of a faint ring -- like Saturn -- going around it. UHC/OIII filters don't help. First time seeing more than just a ball. Cool!
Faint, mottled glow, hints of spiral arms visible. Core is not concentrated. Some bright, stellar spots.

Trans: 2 (not completely dark, and a little hazy from smoke)
Notes: 17 Boo = kappa Boo: wide double. Both primary and secondary have a faint yellow tint. 21 Boo = iota Boo: Even wider, bright double. Secondary has an orange-brown color.
Broomstick is bright and obvious. Other hints of nebulosity throughout the view. Very nice! 52 Cyg is a wide double; secondary seen only with averted vision. Tons of fainter stars not sketched.
Crescent shape, large and bright. Has lots of filaments going up to the West, inside the crescent. Lots of fainter stars not sketched.
6818: looks star-like, fairly bright. Dims somewhat more than nearby stars with direct vision. 6822: very faint and diffuse. Oval shaped. Best seen when moving the scope.

M15: very concentrated, estimate class I. Bright and visible in the finder scope. Pease 1: After several years and numerous attempts, finally saw this! Just a small dot in a particular place. Confirmed by blinking a UHC filter; the spot stayed brighter while everything else dimmed. Instructions from Cloudy Nights forum "Pease 1 using a 16" Lightbridge" for finding this were very helpful.  This took about an hour of effort to find/confirm/sketch.

No filter: see a faint doughnut shaped glow, diffuse. UHC brings this out, also the center gets brighter. OIII shows slightly more detail, but a bit dark and hard to see the stars. Cannot see CS with filter, but was able to see it unfiltered.
Very large, bright. Long and thin. Core is brighter but still diffuse. Elliptical? [no, spiral]
Large, but very faint and diffuse. Easy to miss. Best seen when moving the scope.
Small; core is brighter, outer part is elongated. Should have a dust lane but I can't see it.
Double arcs of stars, like a rainbow, with 4 bright stars on the ends. At the center is NGC 7789, which is very faint, appears as a cloud of very faint stars.
Mirach is bright, has a gold color. NGC 404 makes a nice equilateral triangle with Mirach and another bright star. Very faint, fairly small, like a fingerprint.
Very bright. Seen at low power. Soft ring, medium bright center. No CS seen. Sketched with gel pen and soft white pastel on black paper.

Large and bright. Seen at low power, unfiltered, but not in the finderscope. UHC brings this out quite a bit, OIII shows even more. Shaped like an apple core, inside a larger fainter oval. Sketched with gel pen and soft white pastel on black paper.
Small, somewhat faint. See about 25 stars, fairly concentrated, similar magnitudes.  Often appears as a haze except with careful averted vision.
Right next to Sadr. General Y share. Large variability in magnitudes. Concentrated. About 20 stars.
Extremely faint, very difficult. Just at the edge of detection. See a slightly lighter patch, hints of stars.

With no filter, just a faint hint of nebulosity next to a star. UHC brings this out some. C-shaped, mottled texture, no CS seen. Uneven brightness, one part of the ring is brighter, some parts invisible.  Cool!
Very bright. Saturated orange-yellow. Really stands out.
Bright fuzzy ball. Disappears with direct vision (while similar-magnitude stars do not). Appears almost stellar at lower powers.
Appears stellar in finderscope. Very bright, very concentrated. Sketched with gel pen and soft white pastel on black paper.
Primary is bright, secondary wide split, and fainter. C is quite faint, requires averted vision.
Has a prominent double star near the center of the cluster. Big, sparse, not too concentrated. Medium variety of brightness. About 75 stars.

Seen at 40x as a PN: slightly fuzzy and disappears with direct vision. Very bright. UHC filter doesn't help. At 250x, see bright round fuzzy ball. Center seems to shimmer/dim slightly, so I wonder if there's a faint ring structure. No CS seen.
Fairly rich cluster. Apparent at 40x as a sparkly patch. Slightly concentrated. Med variability in brightnesses, except for one bright star. About 50 stars. Lots of doubles.

All stars white. A bright, B a little dimmer, C faint. Tried this with SV Access 80 also (112x). C was still visible but A, B hard to separate (possible but difficult, required averted vision to see both components). AB sep is 8.7".
A and BC are similar brightness. BC maybe slightly brighter. Can't split B, C; sometimes a hint of elongation.
A, B bright, easily split. D is dim. Can't see C component; should be directly opposite D from A,B.

M31: extremely big, very bright. Can see naked-eye. Core is very bright. Hints of a dust lane. M32: Small, round, fuzzy. Clearly non-stellar. M110: somewhat faint. Core not so concentrated. Oval shape.
Very rich cluster. Stars somewhat uniform in brightness. Not concentrated. Lots of thin dark lanes between stars. Very cool!

7635: Nearly invisible without a filter. OIII helps a little, but UHC brings this out a lot. General nebulosity around several stars, and bright around one. :) M52: Not concentrated, fairly even magnitudes. Can see about 30 stars (with UHC) and a general glow.
No filter-very faint glow. UHC brightens this a lot. (OIII also, but general view is too dim.) Cloud-like glow, irregular shape. Hints of darker dust lanes? Like it!
Invisible without a filter. UHC doesn't help much. OIII brings this out some. General glow around a C-shaped asterism of stars. Rather faint.
A is bright, pale gold color. B fainter, blue gray. C white and maybe 2 magnitudes dimmer than B. Great colored double! Easy.
Always fun! Bright, easy, really looks like an owl. Brightest star is slightly yellow. About 50-60 stars. :)
Parse cluster. Triangular shape with an "egg" of stars in the middle. 15 stars.

8:07: eclipse starts, but cloudy, so can't see the sun. 8:20: first observed. Half of the sun obscured by clouds, but can see a nice chunk taken out. Very dramatic view. 8:29: Clouds have broken. See 3 groups of sunspots. Fair amount of turbulence visible at the edges. 8:50: Moon is covering up past the center of the sun. Can visibly see it move over two minutes as it covers up the first sunspot group. 8:54: fairly thin clouds. Can't see eclipse in the telescope, but can see the sun dimly naked-eye through the clouds. 8:55: fast moving fog, can't see anything. 9:07: Clouds broken again. Moon almost covering up the last group of sunspots. Moon's disc is clearly smaller than the sun. (This is an annular eclipse in Oregon/Texas.) 9:20: Maximum eclipse, 85.8% covered. Near the max, the intersection points of the moon's and sun's edges rotate pretty fast. 9:49: Partially cloudy. Can see a new sunspot group through the clouds.  10:07: fairly thick clouds, difficult to see the sun. 10:26: can see sunspots again, barely. 10:39: end of eclipse. Still cloudy, can see the moon's disc exit.
Crater is light gray, with white dot in the center and white rim. Lots of lunar rays in light gray surrounding it.
Good detail. See 5 bands and some whorls (occasionally). Very cool!

Trans: 4 (clear, cold. Sky dark but lots of lights)
Notes: Very large, bright! 869 has 2 very bright stars, and is concentrated with little loops  of stars near the center. 884 is slightly more spread out; it has two pairs of triangles of stars in the center. A bit difficult to draw. Delos 17 shows a fair amount of coma.

Flat bottom. Rim of crater only extends 2/3 of the way around. Crater filled at the same level as the outside. Bright white dot inside. Rim is white. Interesting round mountain below the crater - rough and has apparent trefoil-shaped valleys.
Large variety of magnitudes. Very large cluster and quite bright. About 60 stars.
Large, bright, and sparkly! About 70 stars. Loose. Large variety of magnitudes. Crouched in the snow to see this.
Large, bright cluster. Somewhat concentrated. Medium variety of magnitudes. Has a general shape of a cross. About 60 stars
Pretty faint for a Messier object. Shape of a butterfly. Need averted vision to see most of the stars. About 30 stars. [Realized I was seeing this through a tree - that was why it was so faint.]
Yoshi cluster! Big, bright, easy to see even at low power. Large variety in magnitudes. About 40 stars. One of my winter favorites!
A bright, B a mag dimmer, C is very faint, averted vision only. Near the Rose Nebula.
Three roughly equal magnitude stars in a neat triangle. Very wide separation; can split at 40x. Like it! Near the Rose Nebula.

Right next to Procyon, easy to find. A, B are very close. Most of the time just a blur, but about 30% of the time see 2 distinct points of light, with a hairline space between them. C is very faint and requires averted vision to see.
Easy to split at low power (40x). Could probably split in the finder scope if brighter. Near another double star.
Can't split A,B. C component is dim, requires averted vision
Can't split A,B. C is dim, just barely seen with direct vision, but easy to see with averted vision.
Not concentrated at the center. Stars similar magnitude. See about 40 stars, all are fairly dim.
Large. Sparse. Not concentrated. About 20 stars, very similar magnitudes.
Stellar at low power. At med and above appears fuzzy. At high power is round, bright , like a class III globular cluster. Center star is obvious. Close to a fairly bright (mag 7) star.

M46: loose, lots of faint stars. (Without filter, see about 60 stars.) Not concentrated. Medium variety of magnitudes. 2438: only seen with filter. Appears as a somewhat faint gray disc. No CS seen. Getting a good view of this has been an elusive challenge for a few years!

Rabbi Levi: has 5 big craterlets, 4 have bright white rims. Crater has somewhat of a pentagonal shape. Zagut: has a large craterlet with a rim that casts a shadow. Also a small mountain. Crater appears very steep. Sketched with black India ink pens.
Complex crater. Has lots of overlapping partial craters on the rim, broken walls. Mountains and hills inside the center and one small craterlet. Sketched with India ink pens.

Herschel: bowl-shaped. Rims have concentric circles. Ptolemaeus: flat, smooth bottom. One small craterlet and several crater-depressions. Very rough, mountainous walls. Alphonsus: flat bottom, but has lots of wrinkly hills/ridges going N/S. Has one small, sharp peak in the center.

Clavius partially in shadow  in this phase. See the first 3 largest craters in the chain of internal craterlets. Also a few hills/mountains and wrinkle ridges in the basin. Very rough walls. Striking shadows. Sketched with India ink pens.

Small. Crescent shape similar to a 5-day moon. Some chromatic aberration from the atmosphere - blue edges on top, red on the bottom. Visible in binoculars but not naked eye. 8:18 - now can see naked-eye.
Fairly bright in the telescope, visible as a very slightly fuzzy star in binoculars. Bright halo around the core. When moving the scope, can see long faint tail as well as a general faint glow.

Atlas: the larger crater. Interior seems a little rough. Has a small hill in the middle. Walls show some concentric cracks, and there is a faint ledge on the N side.  Hercules: partly in shadow. Has a large, deep, bowl-shaped crater. Floor looks smooth and darker compared to Atlas. Crater walls show a prominent step. Drawn with black charcoal on white cardstock.

Rupes Recta is very long and straight. It is a cliff, not a long hill, as the west side is not more brightly illuminated. Soft, wrinkly hills form the E side of the crater; the West side is more rough. Very cool, dramatic shadows close to the terminator! Sketched with pencil on watercolor paper.

Fra Mauro: almost completely filled in crater. Only the top rims appear as soft hills. Flat, smooth bottom. Parry, Bomland: similar, but smaller. The three craters all meet like 3 bubbles touching. Walls on parry are a bit taller.
Fun asterism/multiple stars. 4 brightest stars are quite bright and seen at low power. Faintest star best seen with averted vision.
T CrB, the "Blaze Star" is quite faint, requires averted vision to see. A bit fainter to the reference star  R next to it. R = mag 9.3; T = mag 10.1, epsilon = mag 4.1
This is the most obvious "feature" of the full moon.
This is a bit tricky to see; had to check the lunar observing program notes to see what to look for.
This is my favorite naked-eye lunar "feature". Hard to draw, though.
M81: bright core, big round glow. No details seen. M82: dimmer, requires averted vision but still easy. Long and thin.

Have several neighbors' lights shining very brightly, making observing harder.  M95: a little difficult at this magnification. Core brighter, obvious when moving the scope. M96: brighter, easier. Only see the core. Bugger but more diffuse.
Faint, small. Right behind a star, slightly offset. Core is not brighter; diffuse.
Faint dot. Requires averted vision
Faint orange tinge (a bit easier to see at higher powers). Part of a cool "funnel" asterism. Brightest (apparent) red dwarf in N hemisphere. 8.3 light years away.
Light yellow tint. Bright! Low mass star - 1.1 solar masses.

Mare Marginis (Border Sea): smooth, flat, just an area without craters. Mare Smythii (Smyth's sea): larger, seems slightly darker than the crater-filled areas nearby.  Saw a satellite cross the dark part of the moon. Kind of cool.
Stars very faint. Bright light from neighbor killing the contrast.

Vibrant orange color. Bright red giant, carbon star. One of the reddest stars known. This was less than 3 degrees from zenith, so I just pointed the scope straight up and found it in the finder.  Never done that before!
Very bright, white. Blue giant. High mass main sequence star.  11.4 solar masses.

Saw amazing aurora borealis! Covered most of the sky, very bright. Could see faint greens and pinks, especially nearer the horizon. Comes in cool bands, seem to radiate outward from zenith. Sometimes fairly static, sometimes bright, quick flashes. This is after a major solar storm (Class G4). Last time this magnitude was 2005, so a rare event. Attempted sketch but difficult. Photos captured it better.
Very flat bottom. Rocky, irregular walls. close to the edge of the moon.
Large. Small hill in the center. 2 internal craterlets, and thre more craterlets on the walls. Should have a rima inside, but can't see it. Adjacent to Mare Crisium.
Slightly better sky conditions than the previous two views of this. Easy to spot which dot is Juno.
Nice display of spots! 49 spots in 6 groups.

Trans: 0 (still evening, slight haze around the moon)
Notes: Doesn't look much like a cow to me, but the arch of various mare is pretty clear.
Very bright. Saturated yellow-orange color.  Red giant star.
Very bright and big. Fairly concentrated. Class VI. Bright haze of stars in the middle, many brighter stars resolved. Few chains of stars running through the cluster.
Class F. Very pale yellow. Near Alkaid (last star in the handle of the Big Dipper). Double star. B component is faint and widely separated.
Very wide double star. Both have similar brightness. Both class K.
Large, bright core. Faint hints of spiral arms.
5566 - very bright. core especially, almost starlike. 5560 - faint. Slightly elongated. Not concentrated.
Appears as a tiny sliver at low power. Long, very thin. Bulge in the middle. Mottled texture. Like it! :)
Relatively faint. White. Variable star. Red dwarf.
Very bright. Vibrant orange. Not able to split. Red supergiant.
Part of a distinctive arc of 7 stars. 1.0 solar mass.
Bright white. Maybe a slight bluish tint.  19 solar masses. 3 M years old.
6520: compact, bright. Large variety in magnitudes. See about 15 stars plus a general haze. B 86: dark area near 6520, blacker than the background. Entire field is rich with stars, not drawn.
Primary is vibrant orange-yellow. Secondary is white. Split at 113x. Bright, easy.  Like it!
Bright white. Magnitude 1. Near 3 pairs of double stars.
Starlike at low power. At 250x, bright circular fuzzy ball. No CS seen. UHC filter brings this out some, but dims the general view too much.
Near a V-shaped asterism. White, not very bright. Red dwarf star; brighter in infrared than in visible light.  Closest star to the sun in the northern hemisphere.

At low power looks like a lightly fuzzy star. Hint of a greenish color? At high power, it is a very bright ellipse, solid, though there are hints of a ring structure that blinks in and out with averted vision. UHC brings this out some. No CS seen.
Stars shimmering. Very bright. Clear butterfly asterism from the brightest 6 stars. One, marked, is yellow. About 70 stars. Large range of magnitudes. Not concentrated at the center. Great view!
Bright nebula with 3-spoked dust lanes. Double star in the center. UHC and OIII filters bring this out some. UHC is the brightest view.

M8: spectacular! Amazing nebulosity, dust lanes. Lots of bright stars (many dimmer ones not drawn). UHC brings out nebulosity quite a lot. 6530: cluster in M8. Fairly small, bright. A bit concentrated, medium variety of magnitudes. See about 20 stars.
Very subtle darker areas around a 'y' shaped asterism of 4 brighter stars. Moving the scope confirms the brighter areas.
Near the limb of the moon. Large. Very large peak in the middle. Rough walls, see like double. See some faint lines -- rimae -- on teh E side. The one further South is probably "Petavius Wall".
